{"title_page": "Albert Edward Martin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n'''Albert Edward Martin''' (1876 \u2013 26 July 1936) was an English merchant and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], later [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.\n\n==Date of birth==\nAccording to the source, Leigh Rayment's Peerage Page, Martin was born in 1875 <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Rcommons2.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121219110721/http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Rcommons2.htm |archive-date=19 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> but [[Who's Who (UK)|Who was Who]] gives his date of birth as 1876.<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\">''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> According to the brief obituary in [[The Times]] newspaper, Martin was aged 59 years when he died, which supports the report of his date of birth as 1876.<ref name=\"The Times, 28 July 1936 p16\">The Times, 28 July 1936 p16</ref>\n\n==Family==\nMartin married  Edith Savory in 1909 and they had a son and two daughters.<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" />\n\n==Career==\nMartin was a successful merchant. He was head of a firm in [[Southend-on-Sea]] in [[Essex]].<ref>''The Times House of Commons 1919;'' Politico\u2019s Publishing 2004 p52</ref> He was also a member of the [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]], rising to the rank of Honorary Colonel of the 52nd [[Anti-Aircraft]] Brigade, (T.A) and he was responsible for raising the 156th Battery.<ref name=\"The Times, 28 July 1936 p16\" /> Martin also served as a [[Justice of the Peace]].<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" />\n\n==Politics==\n===Parliamentary candidate, 1918===\nMartin was selected as Liberal candidate for [[Romford (UK Parliament constituency)|Romford]] in Essex to fight the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]] in succession to the sitting Liberal [[Member of Parliament (UK)|MP]], [[John Bethell, 1st Baron Bethell|Sir John Bethell]] who had transferred to the nearby seat of  [[East Ham North (UK Parliament constituency)|East Ham North]]. Both Martin and Bethell were awarded the [[Coalition coupon]] for the election and both were returned. In Romford, Martin faced a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] opponent and one from the left-wing [[National Socialist Party (UK)|National Socialist Party]]. In the absence of a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]], with the Labour vote split and with the endorsement of the coupon, Martin won the seat comfortably with a majority of 5,256 votes.<ref>''The Times House of Commons 1919''; Politico\u2019s Publishing 2004 p52</ref>\n\n===1922===\nAt the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]] Martin stood as a [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1922)|National Liberal]], that is to say as a supporter of outgoing [[Prime Minister]] [[David Lloyd George]] of whose [[Coalition government 1916-1922|Coalition government]] he had been a supporter. Again without a Conservative opponent, Martin was involved in a straight fight against Labour. He held his seat by a majority of 4,103 votes.<ref name=\"S Craig, p355\">F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results, 1918-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 p355</ref>\n\n===1923===\nMartin's years of working with the Conservatives in Parliament and presumably at a local level, must have played a part in his decision in 1923 to leave the Liberals and join the [[Tories]]. As the [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923 general election]] approached Martin was adopted by the Romford Conservatives as their candidate for the contest.<ref>The Times, 17 November 1923 p13</ref> However this move was resented by some in the constituency and this bitterness could have proved problematic for Martin's election campaign. In the event the potential difficulties never presented themselves as Martin withdrew from the fray on the grounds that his health had broken down. The Conservatives  selected another candidate [[Charles Rhys, 8th Baron Dynevor|Charles Rhys]] to represent them <ref>The Times, 24 November 1923 p14</ref> and Rhys went on to win the seat, holding it until [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]].<ref name=\"S Craig, p355\" />\n\n===Local politics===\nMartin continued to enjoy a political career at [[Local government in England|local government]] level. He was Charter [[Mayor]] of the new [[Municipal Borough of Barking]] in 1931  <ref>The Times, 12 August 1931 p7</ref> and was re-elected Mayor in November 1932. He was sometime Chairman of Barking Education Committee and of the Food Control Committee.<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" /> He was also an [[Alderman]] of the Borough.<ref>The Times, 25 January 1933 p12</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMartin died at his home, Oak Hall, The Leas, [[Westcliff-on-Sea]], Essex on 26 July 1936.<ref name=\"The Times, 28 July 1936 p16\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-albert-martin | Albert Martin }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Romford (UK Parliament constituency)|Romford]]\n | years  = [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]] \u2013 [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]]\n | before = [[John Bethell, 1st Baron Bethell|Sir John Bethell]]\n | after  = [[Charles Rhys, 8th Baron Dynevor|Charles Rhys]]\n}}\n{{s-civic}}\n{{succession box|title=Mayor of Barking|years=1931&ndash;1934|before=''New position''|after=Alfred George Edwards}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin, Albert Edward}}\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:English merchants]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Politics of Essex]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Greater London]]\n[[Category:National Liberal Party (UK, 1922) politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n'''Albert Edward Martin''' (1876 \u2013 26 July 1936) was an English merchant and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], later [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.\n\n==Date of birth==\nAccording to the source, Leigh Rayment\u2019s Peerage Page, Martin was born in 1875 <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Rcommons2.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121219110721/http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Rcommons2.htm |archive-date=19 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> but [[Who's Who (UK)|Who was Who]] gives his date of birth as 1876.<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\">''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> According to the brief obituary in [[The Times]] newspaper, Martin was aged 59 years when he died, which supports the report of his date of birth as 1876.<ref name=\"The Times, 28 July 1936 p16\">The Times, 28 July 1936 p16</ref>\n\n==Family==\nMartin married  Edith Savory in 1909 and they had a son and two daughters.<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" />\n\n==Career==\nMartin was a successful merchant. He was head of a firm in [[Southend-on-Sea]] in [[Essex]].<ref>''The Times House of Commons 1919;'' Politico\u2019s Publishing 2004 p52</ref> He was also a member of the [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]], rising to the rank of Honorary Colonel of the 52nd [[Anti-Aircraft]] Brigade, (T.A) and he was responsible for raising the 156th Battery.<ref name=\"The Times, 28 July 1936 p16\" /> Martin also served as a [[Justice of the Peace]].<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" />\n\n==Politics==\n===Parliamentary candidate, 1918===\nMartin was selected as Liberal candidate for [[Romford (UK Parliament constituency)|Romford]] in Essex to fight the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]] in succession to the sitting Liberal [[Member of Parliament (UK)|MP]], [[John Bethell, 1st Baron Bethell|Sir John Bethell]] who had transferred to the nearby seat of  [[East Ham North (UK Parliament constituency)|East Ham North]]. Both Martin and Bethell were awarded the [[Coalition coupon]] for the election and both were returned. In Romford, Martin faced a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] opponent and one from the left-wing [[National Socialist Party (UK)|National Socialist Party]]. In the absence of a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]], with the Labour vote split and with the endorsement of the coupon, Martin won the seat comfortably with a majority of 5,256 votes.<ref>''The Times House of Commons 1919''; Politico\u2019s Publishing 2004 p52</ref>\n\n===1922===\nAt the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]] Martin stood as a [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1922)|National Liberal]], that is to say as a supporter of outgoing [[Prime Minister]] [[David Lloyd George]] of whose [[Coalition government 1916-1922|Coalition government]] he had been a supporter. Again without a Conservative opponent, Martin was involved in a straight fight against Labour. He held his seat by a majority of 4,103 votes.<ref name=\"S Craig, p355\">F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results, 1918-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 p355</ref>\n\n===1923===\nMartin\u2019s years of working with the Conservatives in Parliament and presumably at a local level, must have played a part in his decision in 1923 to leave the Liberals and join the [[Tories]]. As the [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923 general election]] approached Martin was adopted by the Romford Conservatives as their candidate for the contest.<ref>The Times, 17 November 1923 p13</ref> However this move was resented by some in the constituency and this bitterness could have proved problematic for Martin's election campaign. In the event the potential difficulties never presented themselves as Martin withdrew from the fray on the grounds that his health had broken down. The Conservatives  selected another candidate [[Charles Rhys, 8th Baron Dynevor|Charles Rhys]] to represent them <ref>The Times, 24 November 1923 p14</ref> and Rhys went on to win the seat, holding it until [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]].<ref name=\"S Craig, p355\" />\n\n===Local politics===\nMartin continued to enjoy a political career at [[Local government in England|local government]] level. He was Charter [[Mayor]] of the new [[Municipal Borough of Barking]] in 1931  <ref>The Times, 12 August 1931 p7</ref> and was re-elected Mayor in November 1932. He was sometime Chairman of Barking Education Committee and of the Food Control Committee.<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" /> He was also an [[Alderman]] of the Borough.<ref>The Times, 25 January 1933 p12</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMartin died at his home, Oak Hall, The Leas, [[Westcliff-on-Sea]], Essex on 26 July 1936.<ref name=\"The Times, 28 July 1936 p16\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-albert-martin | Albert Martin }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Romford (UK Parliament constituency)|Romford]]\n | years  = [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]] \u2013 [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]]\n | before = [[John Bethell, 1st Baron Bethell|Sir John Bethell]]\n | after  = [[Charles Rhys, 8th Baron Dynevor|Charles Rhys]]\n}}\n{{s-civic}}\n{{succession box|title=Mayor of Barking|years=1931&ndash;1934|before=''New position''|after=Alfred George Edwards}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin, Albert Edward}}\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:English merchants]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Politics of Essex]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Greater London]]\n[[Category:National Liberal Party (UK, 1922) politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Edward_Martin"}
{"title_page": "Constance Markievicz", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Constance Markievicz\n| image = Countess Markiewicz.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption = Constance Markievicz\n| office = [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|Member of Parliament]] for<br>[[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick\u2019s]]\n| predecessor = [[William Field (Irish politician)|William Field]]\n| successor = Constituency abolished\n| term_start = 1918\n| term_end = 1922\n| constituency =\n| office2 = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start2 = December 1918\n| term_end2 = May 1921\n| constituency2 = [[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick's]]\n| term_start3 = May 1921\n| term_end3 = June 1922\n| term_start4 = August 1923\n| term_end4 = July 1927\n| constituency4 = [[Dublin South (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin South]]\n| office5 = [[Minister for Labour (Ireland)|Minister for Labour]]\n| term_start5 = April 1919\n| term_end5 = January 1922\n| predecessor5 = New office\n| successor5 = [[Joseph McGrath (Irish politician)|Joseph McGrath]]\n| birthname = Constance Georgine Gore-Booth\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1868|2|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Buckingham Gate]],<br />London, England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1927|7|15|1868|2|4}}\n| death_place = [[Sir Patrick Dun's Hospital]],<br />[[Dublin]], Ireland\n| party = [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] (1926\u20131927)<br />[[Sinn F\u00e9in]] (1908\u20131926)\n| spouse = [[Casimir Markievicz]] (m. 1900)\n| children = Maeve Markievicz (1901\u20131962)\n| parents = {{Ubl|[[Sir Henry Gore-Booth, 5th Baronet|Sir Henry Gore-Booth]]|Georgina Hill}}\n| relations = [[Eva Gore-Booth]] (Sister)\n| restingplace = [[Glasnevin Cemetery]],<br />[[Dublin]], Ireland\n| allegiance = [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]]<br />[[Irish Citizen Army]]<br />[[Irish Republican Army]]<br />[[Cumann na mBan]]\n| serviceyears = 1913\u20131923\n| rank = Lieutenant<ref>[[Bureau of Military History]], [http://95.45.178.102/reels/bmh/BMH.WS1666.pdf#page=8 Winess Statement 1666] (Fr. T. O'Donoghue), p. 8</ref>\n| commands =\n| unit =\n| battles = [[Dublin Lockout]]<br />[[Easter Rising]]<br />[[Irish War of Independence]]<br />[[Irish Civil War]]\n| awards =\n}}\n\n'''Constance Georgine Markievicz''', known as '''Countess Markievicz''' ({{lang-pl|Markiewicz}} {{IPA-pl|mar\u02c8k\u02b2\u025bvit\u0282|}}; {{n\u00e9e|'''Gore-Booth'''}}; 4 February 1868 \u2013 15 July 1927), was an Irish politician, [[revolutionary]], [[Irish nationalism|nationalist]], [[suffragist]], [[Socialism|socialist]], the first woman elected to the [[Westminster Parliament]], and was elected [[Minister for Labour (Ireland)|Minister for Labour]] in the [[First D\u00e1il]], becoming the first female [[cabinet minister]] in Europe. She served as a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for the [[Dublin South (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin South]] constituency from 1921 to 1922 and 1923 to 1927. She was a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick's]] from 1918 to 1922.\n\nA founder member of [[Fianna \u00c9ireann]], [[Cumann na mBan]] and the [[Irish Citizen Army]], she took part in the [[Easter Rising]] in 1916, when Irish republicans attempted to end British rule and establish an [[Irish Republic]]. She was sentenced to death but this was reduced on the grounds of her sex. [[1918 Irish general election|On 28 December 1918]], she was the first woman elected to the UK [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]],<ref name=dec28 /> though, being in [[Holloway Prison]] at the time and in accordance with party policy, she did not take her seat.  Instead, she and the other Sinn F\u00e9in MPs (as [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TDs]]) formed the [[First D\u00e1il|first]] [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]]. She was also one of the first women in the world to hold a cabinet position, as [[Minister for Labour (Ireland)|Minister for Labour]], from 1919 to 1922.{{efn|name=firstm|[[Alexandra Kollontai]] was [[People's Commissar]] (Minister) for Social Welfare of [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Soviet Russia]] from 1917 to 1918.}}\n\n== Early life ==\nConstance Georgine Gore-Booth was born at [[Buckingham Gate]] in London in 1868, the elder daughter of the Arctic explorer and adventurer [[Sir Henry Gore-Booth, 5th Baronet]], an [[Anglo-Irish]] landlord who administered a {{convert|100|km2|sqmi|abbr=on|lk=off}} estate, and Georgina, Lady Gore-Booth, ''n\u00e9e'' Hill. During the [[Irish Famine (1879)|famine of 1879\u201380]], Sir Henry provided free food for the tenants on his estate at [[Lissadell House]] in the north of [[County Sligo]] in the north-west of Ireland. Their father's example inspired in Gore-Booth and her younger sister, [[Eva Gore-Booth]], a deep concern for working people and the poor. The sisters were childhood friends of the poet [[W. B. Yeats]], who frequently visited the family home Lissadell House, and were influenced by his artistic and political ideas. Yeats wrote a poem, \"[[In Memory of Eva Gore-Booth and Con Markiewicz]]\", in which he described the sisters as \"two girls in silk kimonos, both beautiful, one a gazelle\" (the gazelle being Constance).<ref>{{cite magazine | first=Rosemary |last=Rodgers |title=The Rebel Countess |magazine=[[Irish America (magazine)|Irish America]] |at=June/July 2015. pp. 42\u20133 |date=11 May 2015 |url=https://issuu.com/irishamerica/docs/ia_june_july_2015 |accessdate=22 November 2018|via=[[issuu]]}}{{break}}{{cite web | first=Rosemary |last=Rodgers |title=The Rebel Countess |website=[[Irish America (magazine)|Irish America]] |at=June/July 2015 |date=13 May 2015 |url=https://irishamerica.com/2015/05/the-rebel-countess/ |accessdate=23 November 2018 |via=Irish America website |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123130609/https://irishamerica.com/2015/05/the-rebel-countess/ |archive-date=23 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Eva later became involved in the [[labour movement]] and [[women's suffrage]] in Great Britain, although initially Constance did not share her sister's ideals.\n\nIn 1921, during the [[Treaty debates]], Markievicz claimed that she had been raised by an uncle in [[Cork (city)|Cork]] who was a \"[[Fenian Rising|'67 man]]\", and from whom she had got her republicanism.'<ref>[https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1921-12-17/1/ Dail debates, 17 December 1921]</ref>\n\n== Marriage and early politics ==\nGore-Booth decided to train as a painter, but at the time only one art school in Dublin accepted women students. In 1892, she went to study at the [[Slade School of Art]] in London,<ref name=\"cawip\">{{cite web|url=http://www.qub.ac.uk/cawp/Irish%20bios/TDs_2.htm#markievicz|title=Countess Markievicz (Constance Markievicz)|work=Centre for Advancement of Women in Politics|accessdate=6 June 2008}}</ref> where she lived at the Alexandra House for Art Pupils, [[Kensington Gore]], founded five years before by [[Francis Cook, 1st Viscount of Monserrate|Sir Francis Cook]], a wealthy great-uncle of [[Maud Gonne]]. One of her contemporaries there was [[Blanche Georgiana Vulliamy]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Lindie |last=Naughton |title=Markievicz: A Most Outrageous Rebel |year=2016 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HTFRDQAAQBAJ| page=37 |publisher=Merrion Press |place=Newbridge, Co. Kildare |isbn=978-1-78537-084-7 |accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref> It was at this time that Gore-Booth first became politically active and joined the [[National Union of Women's Suffrage Societies]] (NUWSS). Later she moved to Paris and enrolled at the prestigious [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] where she met her future husband, [[Casimir Markievicz]], an artist from a wealthy [[Poles|Polish]] family from [[Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewildgeese.com/pages/ireland.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19980505065850/http://thewildgeese.com/pages/ireland.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=1998-05-05|title=Constance Markievicz: The Countess of Irish Freedom|work=The Wild Geese today}}</ref> Markievicz was known in Paris as \"Count Markievicz\". When Constance's family enquired as to the validity of the title, they were informed through [[Pyotr Rachkovsky]] of the Russian Secret Police that he had taken the title \"without right\", and that there had never been a \"Count Markievicz\" in Poland.<ref>{{cite book |last=Arrington |first=Lauren |title=Revolutionary Lives: Constance and Casimir Markievicz |year=2015 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=978-1-4008-7418-7 |pages=21\u20132 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZzRJCgAAQBAJ |accessdate=29 March 2016 |place=Princeton, NJ |ref=harv}}</ref>\nHowever, the Department of Genealogy in Saint Petersburg said that he was entitled to claim to be a member of the nobility.{{sfnp|Arrington|2015|p=22 (footnote)}} Markievicz was married, though separated, at the time that they met, but his wife died in 1899 and he and Gore-Booth married in London on 29 September 1900.<ref name=lissadell>{{cite web|url=http://www.constancemarkievicz.ie/marriage.php|title=Constance Georgine Gore-Booth|publisher=The Lissadell Estate|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118172244/http://www.constancemarkievicz.ie/marriage.php|archivedate=18 November 2007|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref> She was afterwards known as \"Countess Markievicz\". She gave birth to their daughter, Maeve, at Lissadell in November 1901.<ref name=lissadell /> The child was raised by her Gore-Booth grandparents and eventually became estranged from her mother. She undertook the role of mother to Stanislas, Casimir's son from his first marriage, who then accompanied the couple to Ireland.\n\nThe Markieviczes settled in [[Dublin]] in 1903 and moved in artistic and literary circles, with Constance gaining a reputation as a landscape painter.<ref>Gore-Booth, Eva, [http://digitalcollections.tcd.ie/home/index.php?folder_id=1020&pidtopage=MS9921_009&entry_point=9 ''The one and the many''], London: Longmans, Green & Co., 1904. Copy with hand-painted illustrations by Constance Markievicz [n\u00e9e Gore-Booth] held in the Manuscripts & Archives Research Library, The Library of Trinity College Dublin. Available in digital form on the Digital Collections website.</ref> In 1905, along with artists [[Sarah Purser]], [[Nathaniel Hone the Younger|Nathaniel Hone]], [[Walter Osborne]] and [[John Butler Yeats]], she was instrumental in founding the United Arts Club, which was an attempt to bring together all those in Dublin with an artistic and literary bent. This group included the leading figures of the [[Gaelic League]] founded by the future first [[President of Ireland]], [[Douglas Hyde]]. Although formally apolitical and concerned with the preservation of the Irish language and culture, the league brought together many patriots and future political leaders. Sarah Purser, whom the young Gore-Booth sisters first met in 1882, when she was commissioned to paint their portrait, hosted a regular salon where artists, writers and intellectuals on both sides of the nationalist divide gathered. At Purser's house, Markievicz met revolutionary patriots [[Michael Davitt]], [[John O'Leary (Fenian)|John O'Leary]] and [[Maud Gonne]]. In 1907, Markievicz rented a cottage in the countryside near Dublin. The previous tenant, the poet [[Padraic Colum]], had left behind copies of ''The Peasant'' and ''Sinn F\u00e9in''. These revolutionary journals promoted independence from [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] rule. Markievicz read these publications and was propelled into action.<ref>Anne Haverty, Constance Markievicz: Irish Revolutionary (Liiliput Press: Dublin, 2016), pp. 73-74.</ref>\n\n[[File:Constance Markievicz statue by Elizabeth McLaughlin (01).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Sculpture of Markievicz and her cocker spaniel, Poppet, on Townsend Street, Dublin]]\n[[File:Constance Markiewicz by John Butler Yeats.jpg|thumb|upright|Sketch of Markievicz by [[John Butler Yeats]]]]\n[[File:countessmarkieviczandchildren.jpg|thumb|upright|Markievicz with her daughter and stepson]]\nIn 1908, Markievicz became actively involved in nationalist politics in Ireland. She joined [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] and [[Inghinidhe na h\u00c9ireann]] ('Daughters of Ireland'), a revolutionary women's movement founded by the actress and activist [[Maud Gonne]], muse of [[William Butler Yeats|W. B. Yeats]]. Markievicz came directly to her first meeting from a function at [[Dublin Castle]], the seat of [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] rule in Ireland, wearing a satin ball-gown and a diamond tiara. Naturally, the members looked upon her with some hostility. This refreshing change from being \"[[kowtow]]ed\"-to as a countess only made her more eager to join.{{Citation needed|reason=How do we know she found this refreshing?|date=March 2016}} She performed with Maud Gonne in several plays at the newly established [[Abbey Theatre]], an institution that played an important part in the rise of cultural nationalism. In the same year, Markievicz played a dramatic role in the women's suffrage campaigners' tactic of opposing [[Winston Churchill]]'s election to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] during the [[1908 Manchester North West by-election|Manchester North West by-election]], flamboyantly appearing in the constituency driving an old-fashioned carriage drawn by four white horses to promote the suffragist cause. A male heckler asked her if she could cook a dinner, to which she responded, \"Yes. Can you drive a coach and four?\" Her sister Eva had moved to Manchester to live with fellow suffragette [[Esther Roper]] and they both campaigned against Churchill with her. Churchill lost the election to Conservative candidate [[William Joynson-Hicks, 1st Viscount Brentford|William Joynson-Hicks]], in part as a result of the suffragists' dedicated opposition.<ref>{{cite book|last=Marecco|first=Anne|title=The Rebel Countess|year=1967|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson}}</ref>\n\nIn 1909 Markievicz and [[Bulmer Hobson]] founded [[Fianna \u00c9ireann]], a [[para-military]] nationalist scouting organisation that instructed teenage boys in the use of firearms. At its first meeting in [[Camden Street, Dublin]], on 16 August 1909, she was almost expelled on the basis that women did not belong in a physical force movement, but Hobson supported her, and she was elected to the committee.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Townshend|first1=Charles|title=Easter 1916: The Irish Rebellion|date=2006|publisher=Penguin Books|location=London|isbn=978-0-14-190276-0|pages=21\u20132|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g6FNKxBJXMYC|accessdate=27 March 2016}}</ref> She was jailed for the first time in 1911 for speaking at an [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]] demonstration attended by 30,000 people, organised to protest against [[George V of the United Kingdom|George V]]'s visit to Ireland. During this protest Markievicz handed out leaflets, erected great masts: ''Dear land thou art not conquered yet.'', participated in stone-throwing at pictures of the King and Queen and attempted to burn the giant British flag taken from [[Leinster House]], eventually succeeding, but then seeing James McArdle imprisoned for one month for the incident, despite Markievicz testifying in court that she was responsible.<ref name=\"Ward_1983_78\">{{cite book |last1=Ward |first1=Margaret |title=Unmanageable Revolutionaries: Women and Irish Nationalism |date=1983 |publisher=Pluto Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-86104-700-0 |page=78 |ref=harv}}</ref> Her friend [[Helena Molony]] was arrested for her part in the stone-throwing and became the first woman in Ireland to be tried and imprisoned for a political act since the time of the [[Fanny Parnell#Ladies' Land League|Ladies Land League]].<ref name=\"Ward_1983_78\" />\n\nMarkievicz also joined [[James Connolly]]'s socialist [[Irish Citizen Army]] (ICA), a small volunteer force formed in response to the [[Dublin Lockout|lock-out]] of 1913, to defend the demonstrating workers from the police. Markievicz recruited volunteers to peel potatoes in a basement while she and others worked on distributing the food. As all the food was paid out of her own pocket,{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}} Markievicz was forced to take out many loans, at this time, and sold all her jewellery. That same year, with Inghinidhe na h\u00c9ireann, she ran a soup kitchen to feed poor school children.\n\nFashion advice attributed to her was: \"Dress suitably in short skirts and strong boots, leave your jewels in the bank and buy a revolver.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Sigillito|first=Gina|title=The Daughters of Maeve: 50 Irish Women Who Changed World|date=2007|publisher=Kensington Publishing Corp.|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8065-3609-5|page=87|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XfUCl5tHDNUC&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Easter Rising ==\n[[File:Countess Markievicz.jpg|thumb|left|Markievicz in uniform examining a [[Colt New Service]] Model 1909 revolver, posed c.1915]]\nIn 1913 Markievicz's husband moved back to Ukraine, and never returned to live in Ireland. However, they did correspond and he was by her side when she died in 1927. As a member of the ICA, Markievicz took part in the 1916 [[Easter Rising]]. She was deeply inspired by the founder of the [[Irish Citizen Army|ICA]], [[James Connolly]]. Markievicz designed the Citizen Army uniform and composed its anthem, based on the tune of a Polish song.<ref>{{cite book|last=Markievicz|first=Constance|title=A Battle Hymn|date=c. 1917|publisher=Irish Traditional Music Archive|url=http://www.itma.ie/digitallibrary/book/battle-hymn|accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the Rising, Markievicz fought in [[St Stephen's Green]], where on the first morning\u2014according to one account\u2014she shot a member of the (unarmed) [[Dublin Metropolitan Police]], Constable Lahiff, who subsequently died of his injuries.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Matthews|first1=Ann|title=Renegades: Irish Republican Women 1900\u20131922|date=2010|publisher=Mercier Press Ltd.|isbn=978-1-85635-684-8|pages=129\u201330|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pzYkTYi3JRgC&pg=PA129|accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Arrington |first=Lauren |url=http://irishhistoriansinbritain.org/?p=18 |title=Did Constance Markievicz Shoot the Policeman? |website=Conference of Irish Historians in Britain}}</ref>\nDistrict nurse Geraldine Fitzgerald, recorded in her diary that as she was returning from duty to the nurses' home, located at the southwest corner of the Green, she saw:\n\n{{quote|A lady in a green uniform, the same as the men were wearing (breeches, slouch hat with green feathers etc.) the feathers were the only feminine feature in her appearance, holding a revolver in one hand and a cigarette in the other, was standing on the footpath giving orders to the men. We recognized her as the Countess de Markievicz \u2013 such a specimen of womanhood. There were other women, similarly attired, inside the Park, walking about and bringing drinks of water to the men. We had only been looking out a few minutes when we saw a policeman walking down the path from Harcourt Street. He had only gone a short way when we heard a shot and then saw him fall forward on his face. The Countess ran triumphantly into the Green saying \u201cI got him\u201d and some of the rebels shook her by the hand and seemed to congratulate her.<ref>Geraldine Fitzgerald, extract from diary in Castle File no. 84 (Constance Markievicz), NA, WO 35/207</ref>}}\n\nOther accounts place her at [[City Hall, Dublin|City Hall]] when the policeman was shot, only arriving at Stephen's Green later.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Constance Markievicz: Irish Revolutionary |last=Haverty |first=Anne |author-link=Anne Haverty|year=1988 |publisher=Pandora |location=London |isbn=978-0-86358-161-8 |page=148 }}</ref> It was long thought that she was second in command to [[Michael Mallin]],{{sfnp|Ward|1983|p=112}} but in fact it was [[Christopher \"Kit\" Poole]] who held that position.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Millar|first1=Scott|title=Not for fame or for name|journal=Liberty|date=December 2013|volume=12|issue=10|page=23}}</ref> Markievicz supervised the setting-up of barricades on Easter Monday and was in the middle of the fighting all around Stephen's Green, wounding a [[British army]] sniper.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McKenna|first1=Joseph|title=Guerrilla Warfare in the Irish War of Independence, 1919\u20131921|date=2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8519-2|page=112|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BxLb0aZOFOMC&pg=PA112|accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref> Trenches were dug in the Green, sheltered by the front gate; however, after British machine gun and rifle fire from the rooftops of tall buildings on the north side of the Green including the Shelbourne Hotel, the Citizen Army troops withdrew to the [[Royal College of Surgeons in Ireland|Royal College of Surgeons]] on the west side of the Green.\n\nThe Stephen's Green garrison held out for six days, ending the engagement when the British brought them a copy of Pearse's surrender order. The British officer, Captain (later Major) de Courcy Wheeler, who accepted their surrender was married to Markievicz's first cousin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mauser pistol handed to me by Countess Markievicz when she surrendered to me at the College of Surgeons Dublin in 1916 with Commandant Mallin. H. E. de C. Wheeler. This was presented to me by General Lowe| url=http://catalogue.nli.ie/Record/vtls000652512/HierarchyTree|website=Catalogue|publisher=National Library of Ireland|accessdate=5 January 2016| date=1916}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bunbury|first1=Turtle|title=Dorothea Findlater \u2013 One Hundred Years On|url=http://www.turtlebunbury.com/interviews/interviews_misc/interviews_misc_dorotheafindlater.html|accessdate=5 January 2016|quote=Perhaps the most awkward arrest Wheeler made was Countess Markievicz, his wife\u2019s first cousin.}}</ref>\n\nThey were taken to Dublin Castle and Markievicz was transported to [[Kilmainham Gaol]]. They were jeered by the crowds as they walked through the streets of Dublin. There, she was the only one of 70 women prisoners who was put into solitary confinement. At her court martial on 4 May 1916, Markievicz pleaded not guilty to \"taking part in an armed rebellion...for the purpose of assisting the enemy,\" but pleaded guilty to having attempted \"to cause disaffection among the civil population of His Majesty\".<ref name=\"FoyBarton303\">{{cite book|last1=Foy|first1=Michael T.|last2=Barton|first2=Brian|title=The Easter Rising|date=2011|publisher=The History Press|isbn=978-0-7524-7272-0|page=303|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wUI7AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA303|accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref>  Markievicz told the court, \"I went out to fight for Ireland's freedom and it does not matter what happens to me. I did what I thought was right and I stand by it.\"<ref name=FoyBarton303 />{{sfnp|Arrington|2015|p=141}} She was sentenced to death, but the court recommended mercy \"solely and only on account of her sex\".<ref name=FoyBarton303 /> The sentence was commuted to life in prison. When told of this, she said to her captors, \"I do wish your lot had the decency to shoot me\".{{efn|In 1939, 2-Lt William Wylie KC, the prosecutor, published a dissenting account that she \"curled up completely\", \"never stopped moaning\" and cried \"I am only a woman, and you cannot shoot a woman.  You must not shoot a woman.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Richardson |first=Neil |title=According to their Lights: Stories of Irishmen in the British Army, Easter 1916 |publisher=The Collins Press |location=Cork |date=2015 |chapter=Chapter 8: Dublin University Officer Training Corps: The Defence of Trinity College Dublin |isbn=978-1-84889-214-9}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dowler|first1=Lorraine|editor1-last=Flint|editor1-first=Colin|title=The Geography of War and Peace: From Death Camps to Diplomats|date=2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-534751-7|page=144|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Za08XQfp3ZwC&pg=PA144&|accessdate=30 March 2016|chapter=Amazonian Landscapes: Gender, War, and Historical Repetition}}</ref>\n\nMarkievicz was transferred to [[Mountjoy Prison]] and then to [[HM Prison Aylesbury|Aylesbury Prison]] in England in July 1916. She was released from prison in 1917, along with others involved in the Rising, as the government in London granted a general amnesty for those who had participated in it. It was around this time that Markievicz, born into the [[Church of Ireland]], converted to [[Catholicism]].\n\n== First D\u00e1il ==\n[[File:Following the pipers! (29677821546).jpg|thumb|Election victory procession led by Markievicz in [[County Clare]] ]]\nIn 1918, she was jailed again for her part in anti-conscription activities. At the [[1918 Irish general election|1918 general election]], Markievicz was elected for the constituency of [[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick's]], beating her opponent [[William Field (Irish politician)|William Field]] with 66% of the vote, as one of 73 [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MPs]]. The results were called on 28 December 1918.<ref name=dec28>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishlabourhistorysociety.com/pdf/Markievicz.pdf|title=Countess Markievicz\u2014'The Rebel Countess'|website=Irish Labour History Society|access-date=17 December 2017}}</ref> This made her the first woman elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom House of Commons]]. However, in line with Sinn F\u00e9in [[abstentionism|abstentionist]] policy, she did not take her seat in the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Archives \u2013 The First Women MPs |website=UK Parliament |url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/parliamentary-archives/explore-guides-to-documentary-archive-/archives-highlights/archives-the-suffragettes/archives-the-first-women-in-parliament-1919-1945 |accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nMarkievicz was in [[Holloway (HM Prison)|Holloway prison]], when her colleagues assembled in Dublin at the first meeting of the [[First D\u00e1il]], the Parliament of the revolutionary [[Irish Republic]]. When her name was called, she was described, like many of those elected, as being \"imprisoned by the foreign enemy\" (''f\u00e9 ghlas ag Gallaibh'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishresistancebooks.com/internment/intern6.htm|title=Internment \u2013 Women Internees 1916\u20131973|first=John |last=McGuffin|year=1973\n|accessdate=22 March 2009}}</ref> She was re-elected to the [[Second D\u00e1il]] in the [[1921 Irish elections|elections of 1921]].<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?id=994|title=Countess Constance de Markievicz|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=22 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nMarkievicz served as [[Minister for Labour (Ireland)|Minister for Labour]] from April 1919 to January 1922, in the [[Government of the 1st D\u00e1il#Second Ministry|Second Ministry]] and the [[Government of the 2nd D\u00e1il#Third Ministry|Third Ministry]] of the D\u00e1il. Holding cabinet rank from April to August 1919, she became both the first Irish female [[Cabinet (government)|Cabinet Minister]] and at the same time, only the second female government minister in Europe.{{efn|name=firstm}}{{sfnp|Ward|1983|p=137}} She was the only female cabinet minister in [[History of Ireland|Irish history]] until 1979 when [[M\u00e1ire Geoghegan-Quinn]] was appointed to the cabinet post of [[Minister for Community, Rural and Gaeltacht Affairs|Minister for the Gaeltacht]] for Fianna F\u00e1il.\n\n== Civil War and Fianna F\u00e1il ==\n[[File:Constance Markiewicz in st stephens green.JPG|thumb|upright|The bust of Constance Markievicz in [[St Stephen's Green]] in Dublin.]]\nMarkievicz left government in January 1922 along with [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] and others in opposition to the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]]. She fought actively for the [[Irish republicanism|Republican]] cause in the [[Irish Civil War]], including the occupation of Moran's Hotel in Dublin. After the War she toured the United States. She was not elected in the [[1922 Irish general election]] but was returned in the [[1923 Irish general election|1923 general election]] for the [[Dublin South (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin South]] constituency. In common with other [[Irish republicanism|Republican]] candidates, she did not take her D\u00e1il seat. She was arrested again in November 1923. In prison, she went on hunger strike, and within a month, she and other prisoners were released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dib.cambridge.org/viewReadPage.do?articleId=a5452|last=Pa\u0161eta|first=Senia|title=Markievicz, Constance Georgine|website=Dictionary of Irish Biography|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe left Sinn F\u00e9in and joined the new [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] party on its foundation in 1926, chairing the inaugural meeting of the new party in La Scala Theatre. In the [[June 1927 Irish general election|June 1927 general election]], she was re-elected to the [[5th D\u00e1il]] as a candidate for Fianna F\u00e1il, which was pledged to return to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]], but died only five weeks later, before she could take her seat.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Co%EF%BB%BFnstance-Georgina-de-Markievicz.D.1919-01-21/|title=Constance Georgina de Markievicz |website=Houses of the Oireachtas |accessdate=23 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123131545/https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Co%EF%BB%BFnstance-Georgina-de-Markievicz.D.1919-01-21/ |archive-date=23 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Her fellow Fianna F\u00e1il TDs signed the controversial [[Oath of Allegiance (Ireland)|Oath of Allegiance]] and took their seats in the D\u00e1il on 12 August 1927, less than a month after her death.<ref>[https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1927-08-12/2/ New Deputies take their seats \u2013 D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann debate \u2013 Friday, 12 Aug 1927]</ref> The party leader \u00c9amon de Valera described the Oath as \"an empty political formula\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/ashorthistory/archive/intro236.shtml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820044651/http://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/ashorthistory/archive/intro236.shtml |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 August 2010 |title=BBC's Short History of Ireland |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=21 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nMarkievicz died at the age of 59 on 15 July 1927, of complications related to [[appendicitis]]. She had given away the last of her wealth, and died in a public ward \"among the poor where she wanted to be\".<ref name=Depuis>{{cite book|last=Depuis|first=Nicola|title=Mn\u00e1 Na H\u00c9ireann: Women who Shaped Ireland|date=2009|publisher=Mercier Press Ltd|location=Cork|isbn=978-1-85635-645-9|page=171|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=heeon5xC5KwC&pg=PA171#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Levenson|first1=Leah|last2=Natterstad|first2=Jerry H.|title=Hanna Sheehy-Skeffington: Irish Feminist|date=1989|publisher=Syracuse University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8156-2480-6|page=452|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MCJO7AX9tjsC&pg=PA152#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref> One of the doctors attending her was her revolutionary colleague, [[Kathleen Lynn]].<ref name=II1927>{{cite news|title=Death of Madame Marcievicz|newspaper=Irish Independent|date=15 July 1927}}</ref> Also at her bedside were Casimir and Stanislas Markievicz, \u00c9amon de Valera and [[Hanna Sheehy-Skeffington]].<ref name=II1927 /> Refused a state funeral by the [[Irish Free State|Free State]] government, she was buried at [[Glasnevin Cemetery]], Dublin, and de Valera gave the funeral oration.<ref name=Depuis /><ref>{{cite news|title=The Late Madame Marcievicz: An Impressive Funeral|newspaper=Irish Independent|date=18 July 1927}}</ref>\n\n[[Se\u00e1n O'Casey]] said of her: \"One thing she had in abundance\u2014physical courage; with that she was clothed as with a garment.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Ratcliffe|first=Susan|title=People on People: The Oxford Dictionary of Biographical Quotations|date=2001|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-866261-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/peopleonpeopleox0000unse/page/235 235]|url=https://archive.org/details/peopleonpeopleox0000unse/page/235}}</ref>\n[[File:Constance Markievicz 1.jpg|thumb|A Dublin City Council 1916 Commemorative plaque, unveiled on 15 July 2019, to commemorate Constance Markievicz and the house she lived in from 1912\u20131916]]\n\n== Tributes ==\nIn 2018 a portrait of Markievicz was donated by the Irish government to the British House of Commons to commemorate the [[Representation of the People Act 1918|1918 Representation of the People Act]], in which, some women were allowed the right to vote for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/press-centre/press-releases/20180719-picture-of-constance-markievicz-first-woman-elected-to-house-of-commons-gifted-to-uk-by-ceann-comhairle|title=Picture of Constance Markievicz, first woman elected to House of Commons, gifted to UK by Ceann Comhairle \u2013 19 Jul 2018, 11.20 \u2013 Houses of the Oireachtas|last=Oireachtas|first=Houses of the|date=2018-07-19|website=www.oireachtas.ie|language=en-ie|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 a Dublin City Council Commemorative Plaque was unveiled at Markievicz's former home in Rathmines, which is Surrey House on Leinster Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dublingazette.com/news/news-city-edition/markievicz-plaque-89230/ |title=Countess Markievicz is honoured with a plaque at Rathmines home |publisher=Dublingazette.com |date= |accessdate=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Portal|Politics}}\n{{Notes}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|first=Se\u00e1n|last= O'Faolain|title=Constance Markievicz|date=1934}}\n* {{cite book|first=Damian|last= Lawlor|title=Na Fianna \u00c9ireann and the Irish Revolution- 1909\u20131923|date=2009}}\n* {{cite book|first=Anne|last= Marreco|author-link=Anne Wignall|title=The Rebel Countess: The Life and Times of Constance Markievicz|date=1967}}\n* {{cite book|first=Diana|last= Norman|title=Terrible Beauty: A Life of Constance Markievicz, 1868\u20131927|date=1987}}\n* {{cite book|first=Anne|last= Haverty|author-link=Anne Haverty|title=Constance Markievicz: Irish Revolutionary|date=1993}}\n* {{cite book|first=Joe|last= McGowan|title=Constance Markievicz: The People's Countess|date=2003}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacqueline|last= Van Voris|title=Constance de Markievicz: In The Cause of Ireland|date=1967}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Constance Markiewicz|Constance Markievicz}}\n* [http://www.sligoheritage.com/archMark.htm Article on Constance Markievicz]\n* [https://digital.library.villanova.edu/Item/vudl:526517 \u2018Women, ideals and the nation\u2019] speech available from the [https://digital.library.villanova.edu/ Digital Library@Villanova University]\n* [http://www.ucc.ie/celt/published/E900003-001/ Her speeches in the Treaty Debates]\n* [http://our-ireland.com/the-irish-rebel-countess-markievicz/ Life As A Rebel & Co-Founder of The Irish Citizen's Army]\n* [http://www.easter1916.ie/index.php/people/a-z/countess-constance-markievicz/ Countess Markievicz and Easter 1916]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[William Field (Irish politician)|William Field]]<br /><small>([[Irish Parliamentary Party]])</small>}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick's]]\n       |years  = 1918\u20131922}}\n{{s-non|reason = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = {{nowrap|[[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick's]]}}\n       |years  = 1918\u20131921}}\n{{s-non|reason = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] Teachta D\u00e1la for [[Dublin South (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin South]]\n       |years  = 1921\u20131922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Myles Keogh (Irish politician)|Myles Keogh]]<br /><small>([[Independent (politician)|Independent]])</small>}}\n{{s-bef|before = New seat in constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] Teachta D\u00e1la for Dublin South\n       |years  = 1923\u20131927}}\n{{s-aft|after  = Herself|as = a Fianna F\u00e1il TD}}\n{{s-bef|before =  Herself|as = a Sinn F\u00e9in TD}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] Teachta D\u00e1la for Dublin South\n       |years  = June\u2013July 1927}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Thomas Hennessy]]<br /><small>([[Cumann na nGaedheal]])</small>}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Labour (Ireland)|Minister for Labour]]\n       |years  = 1919\u20131922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Joseph McGrath (Irish politician)|Joseph McGrath]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{2nd Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{3rd Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{Easter Rising}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Markievicz, Constance}}\n[[Category:1868 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]\n[[Category:British female MPs]]\n[[Category:British suffragists]]\n[[Category:Burials at Glasnevin Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Catholic socialists]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism from Anglicanism]]\n[[Category:Cumann na mBan members]]\n[[Category:Daughters of baronets]]\n[[Category:Early Sinn F\u00e9in TDs]]\n[[Category:Fianna F\u00e1il TDs]]\n[[Category:Gore family (Anglo-Irish aristocracy)|Constance]]\n[[Category:Irish Citizen Army members]]\n[[Category:Irish revolutionaries]]\n[[Category:Members of the 1st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 4th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 5th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Dublin constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:People of the Easter Rising]]\n[[Category:People of the Irish Civil War (Anti-Treaty side)]]\n[[Category:Polish nobility]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Sligo]]\n[[Category:Socialist feminists]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:Women Teachta\u00ed D\u00e1la]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Women in war 1900\u20131945]]\n[[Category:Women in war in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Women of the Victorian era]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Constance Markievicz\n| image = Countess Markiewicz.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption = Constance Markievicz\n| office = [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|Member of Parliament]] for<br>[[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick\u2019s]]\n| predecessor = [[William Field (Irish politician)|William Field]]\n| successor = Constituency abolished\n| term_start = 1918\n| term_end = 1922\n| constituency =\n| office2 = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start2 = December 1918\n| term_end2 = May 1921\n| constituency2 = [[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick's]]\n| term_start3 = May 1921\n| term_end3 = June 1922\n| term_start4 = August 1923\n| term_end4 = July 1927\n| constituency4 = [[Dublin South (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin South]]\n| office5 = [[Minister for Labour (Ireland)|Minister for Labour]]\n| term_start5 = April 1919\n| term_end5 = January 1922\n| predecessor5 = New office\n| successor5 = [[Joseph McGrath (Irish politician)|Joseph McGrath]]\n| birthname = Constance Georgine Gore-Booth\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1868|2|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Buckingham Gate]],<br />London, England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1927|7|15|1868|2|4}}\n| death_place = [[Sir Patrick Dun's Hospital]],<br />[[Dublin]], Ireland\n| party = [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] (1926\u20131927)<br />[[Sinn F\u00e9in]] (1908\u20131926)\n| spouse = [[Casimir Markievicz]] (m. 1900)\n| children = Maeve Markievicz (1901\u20131962)\n| parents = {{Ubl|[[Sir Henry Gore-Booth, 5th Baronet|Sir Henry Gore-Booth]]|Georgina Hill}}\n| relations = [[Eva Gore-Booth]] (Sister)\n| restingplace = [[Glasnevin Cemetery]],<br />[[Dublin]], Ireland\n| allegiance = [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]]<br />[[Irish Citizen Army]]<br />[[Irish Republican Army]]<br />[[Cumann na mBan]]\n| serviceyears = 1913\u20131923\n| rank = Lieutenant<ref>[[Bureau of Military History]], [http://95.45.178.102/reels/bmh/BMH.WS1666.pdf#page=8 Winess Statement 1666] (Fr. T. O'Donoghue), p. 8</ref>\n| commands =\n| unit =\n| battles = [[Dublin Lockout]]<br />[[Easter Rising]]<br />[[Irish War of Independence]]<br />[[Irish Civil War]]\n| awards =\n}}\n\n'''Constance Georgine Markievicz''', known as '''Countess Markievicz''' ({{lang-pl|Markiewicz}} {{IPA-pl|mar\u02c8k\u02b2\u025bvit\u0282|}}; {{n\u00e9e|'''Gore-Booth'''}}; 4 February 1868 \u2013 15 July 1927), was an Irish politician, [[revolutionary]], [[Irish nationalism|nationalist]], [[suffragist]], [[Socialism|socialist]], the first woman elected to the [[Westminster Parliament]], and was elected [[Minister for Labour (Ireland)|Minister for Labour]] in the [[First D\u00e1il]], becoming the first female [[cabinet minister]] in Europe. She served as a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for the [[Dublin South (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin South]] constituency from 1921 to 1922 and 1923 to 1927. She was a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick's]] from 1918 to 1922.\n\nA founder member of [[Fianna \u00c9ireann]], [[Cumann na mBan]] and the [[Irish Citizen Army]], she took part in the [[Easter Rising]] in 1916, when Irish republicans attempted to end British rule and establish an [[Irish Republic]]. She was sentenced to death but this was reduced on the grounds of her sex. [[1918 Irish general election|On 28 December 1918]], she was the first woman elected to the UK [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]],<ref name=dec28 /> though, being in [[Holloway Prison]] at the time and in accordance with party policy, she did not take her seat.  Instead, she and the other Sinn F\u00e9in MPs (as [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TDs]]) formed the [[First D\u00e1il|first]] [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]]. She was also one of the first women in the world to hold a cabinet position, as [[Minister for Labour (Ireland)|Minister for Labour]], from 1919 to 1922.{{efn|name=firstm|[[Alexandra Kollontai]] was [[People's Commissar]] (Minister) for Social Welfare of [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Soviet Russia]] from 1917 to 1918.}}\n\n== Early life ==\nConstance Georgine Gore-Booth was born at [[Buckingham Gate]] in London in 1868, the elder daughter of the Arctic explorer and adventurer [[Sir Henry Gore-Booth, 5th Baronet]], an [[Anglo-Irish]] landlord who administered a {{convert|100|km2|sqmi|abbr=on|lk=off}} estate, and Georgina, Lady Gore-Booth, ''n\u00e9e'' Hill. During the [[Irish Famine (1879)|famine of 1879\u201380]], Sir Henry provided free food for the tenants on his estate at [[Lissadell House]] in the north of [[County Sligo]] in the north-west of Ireland. Their father's example inspired in Gore-Booth and her younger sister, [[Eva Gore-Booth]], a deep concern for working people and the poor. The sisters were childhood friends of the poet [[W. B. Yeats]], who frequently visited the family home Lissadell House, and were influenced by his artistic and political ideas. Yeats wrote a poem, \"[[In Memory of Eva Gore-Booth and Con Markiewicz]]\", in which he described the sisters as \"two girls in silk kimonos, both beautiful, one a gazelle\" (the gazelle being Constance).<ref>{{cite magazine | first=Rosemary |last=Rodgers |title=The Rebel Countess |magazine=[[Irish America (magazine)|Irish America]] |at=June/July 2015. pp. 42\u20133 |date=11 May 2015 |url=https://issuu.com/irishamerica/docs/ia_june_july_2015 |accessdate=22 November 2018|via=[[issuu]]}}{{break}}{{cite web | first=Rosemary |last=Rodgers |title=The Rebel Countess |website=[[Irish America (magazine)|Irish America]] |at=June/July 2015 |date=13 May 2015 |url=https://irishamerica.com/2015/05/the-rebel-countess/ |accessdate=23 November 2018 |via=Irish America website |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123130609/https://irishamerica.com/2015/05/the-rebel-countess/ |archive-date=23 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Eva later became involved in the [[labour movement]] and [[women's suffrage]] in Great Britain, although initially Constance did not share her sister's ideals.\n\nIn 1921, during the [[Treaty debates]], Markievicz claimed that she had been raised by an uncle in [[Cork (city)|Cork]] who was a \"[[Fenian Rising|'67 man]]\", and from whom she had got her republicanism.'<ref>[https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1921-12-17/1/ Dail debates, 17 December 1921]</ref>\n\n== Marriage and early politics ==\nGore-Booth decided to train as a painter, but at the time only one art school in Dublin accepted women students. In 1892, she went to study at the [[Slade School of Art]] in London,<ref name=\"cawip\">{{cite web|url=http://www.qub.ac.uk/cawp/Irish%20bios/TDs_2.htm#markievicz|title=Countess Markievicz (Constance Markievicz)|work=Centre for Advancement of Women in Politics|accessdate=6 June 2008}}</ref> where she lived at the Alexandra House for Art Pupils, [[Kensington Gore]], founded five years before by [[Francis Cook, 1st Viscount of Monserrate|Sir Francis Cook]], a wealthy great-uncle of [[Maud Gonne]]. One of her contemporaries there was [[Blanche Georgiana Vulliamy]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Lindie |last=Naughton |title=Markievicz: A Most Outrageous Rebel |year=2016 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HTFRDQAAQBAJ| page=37 |publisher=Merrion Press |place=Newbridge, Co. Kildare |isbn=978-1-78537-084-7 |accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref> It was at this time that Gore-Booth first became politically active and joined the [[National Union of Women's Suffrage Societies]] (NUWSS). Later she moved to Paris and enrolled at the prestigious [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] where she met her future husband, [[Casimir Markievicz]], an artist from a wealthy [[Poles|Polish]] family from [[Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewildgeese.com/pages/ireland.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19980505065850/http://thewildgeese.com/pages/ireland.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=1998-05-05|title=Constance Markievicz: The Countess of Irish Freedom|work=The Wild Geese today}}</ref> Markievicz was known in Paris as \"Count Markievicz\". When Constance's family enquired as to the validity of the title, they were informed through [[Pyotr Rachkovsky]] of the Russian Secret Police that he had taken the title \"without right\", and that there had never been a \"Count Markievicz\" in Poland.<ref>{{cite book |last=Arrington |first=Lauren |title=Revolutionary Lives: Constance and Casimir Markievicz |year=2015 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=978-1-4008-7418-7 |pages=21\u20132 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZzRJCgAAQBAJ |accessdate=29 March 2016 |place=Princeton, NJ |ref=harv}}</ref>\nHowever, the Department of Genealogy in Saint Petersburg said that he was entitled to claim to be a member of the nobility.{{sfnp|Arrington|2015|p=22 (footnote)}} Markievicz was married, though separated, at the time that they met, but his wife died in 1899 and he and Gore-Booth married in London on 29 September 1900.<ref name=lissadell>{{cite web|url=http://www.constancemarkievicz.ie/marriage.php|title=Constance Georgine Gore-Booth|publisher=The Lissadell Estate|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118172244/http://www.constancemarkievicz.ie/marriage.php|archivedate=18 November 2007|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref> She was afterwards known as \"Countess Markievicz\". She gave birth to their daughter, Maeve, at Lissadell in November 1901.<ref name=lissadell /> The child was raised by her Gore-Booth grandparents and eventually became estranged from her mother. She undertook the role of mother to Stanislas, Casimir's son from his first marriage, who then accompanied the couple to Ireland.\n\nThe Markieviczes settled in [[Dublin]] in 1903 and moved in artistic and literary circles, with Constance gaining a reputation as a landscape painter.<ref>Gore-Booth, Eva, [http://digitalcollections.tcd.ie/home/index.php?folder_id=1020&pidtopage=MS9921_009&entry_point=9 ''The one and the many''], London: Longmans, Green & Co., 1904. Copy with hand-painted illustrations by Constance Markievicz [n\u00e9e Gore-Booth] held in the Manuscripts & Archives Research Library, The Library of Trinity College Dublin. Available in digital form on the Digital Collections website.</ref> In 1905, along with artists [[Sarah Purser]], [[Nathaniel Hone the Younger|Nathaniel Hone]], [[Walter Osborne]] and [[John Butler Yeats]], she was instrumental in founding the United Arts Club, which was an attempt to bring together all those in Dublin with an artistic and literary bent. This group included the leading figures of the [[Gaelic League]] founded by the future first [[President of Ireland]], [[Douglas Hyde]]. Although formally apolitical and concerned with the preservation of the Irish language and culture, the league brought together many patriots and future political leaders. Sarah Purser, whom the young Gore-Booth sisters first met in 1882, when she was commissioned to paint their portrait, hosted a regular salon where artists, writers and intellectuals on both sides of the nationalist divide gathered. At Purser's house, Markievicz met revolutionary patriots [[Michael Davitt]], [[John O'Leary (Fenian)|John O'Leary]] and [[Maud Gonne]]. In 1907, Markievicz rented a cottage in the countryside near Dublin. The previous tenant, the poet [[Padraic Colum]], had left behind copies of ''The Peasant'' and ''Sinn F\u00e9in''. These revolutionary journals promoted independence from [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] rule. Markievicz read these publications and was propelled into action.<ref>Anne Haverty, Constance Markievicz: Irish Revolutionary (Liiliput Press: Dublin, 2016), pp. 73-74.</ref>\n\n[[File:Constance Markievicz statue by Elizabeth McLaughlin (01).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Sculpture of Markievicz and her cocker spaniel, Poppet, on Townsend Street, Dublin]]\n[[File:Constance Markiewicz by John Butler Yeats.jpg|thumb|upright|Sketch of Markievicz by [[John Butler Yeats]]]]\n[[File:countessmarkieviczandchildren.jpg|thumb|upright|Markievicz with her daughter and stepson]]\nIn 1908, Markievicz became actively involved in nationalist politics in Ireland. She joined [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] and [[Inghinidhe na h\u00c9ireann]] ('Daughters of Ireland'), a revolutionary women's movement founded by the actress and activist [[Maud Gonne]], muse of [[William Butler Yeats|W. B. Yeats]]. Markievicz came directly to her first meeting from a function at [[Dublin Castle]], the seat of [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] rule in Ireland, wearing a satin ball-gown and a diamond tiara. Naturally, the members looked upon her with some hostility. This refreshing change from being \"[[kowtow]]ed\"-to as a countess only made her more eager to join.{{Citation needed|reason=How do we know she found this refreshing?|date=March 2016}} She performed with Maud Gonne in several plays at the newly established [[Abbey Theatre]], an institution that played an important part in the rise of cultural nationalism. In the same year, Markievicz played a dramatic role in the women's suffrage campaigners' tactic of opposing [[Winston Churchill]]'s election to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] during the [[1908 Manchester North West by-election|Manchester North West by-election]], flamboyantly appearing in the constituency driving an old-fashioned carriage drawn by four white horses to promote the suffragist cause. A male heckler asked her if she could cook a dinner, to which she responded, \"Yes. Can you drive a coach and four?\" Her sister Eva had moved to Manchester to live with fellow suffragette [[Esther Roper]] and they both campaigned against Churchill with her. Churchill lost the election to Conservative candidate [[William Joynson-Hicks, 1st Viscount Brentford|William Joynson-Hicks]], in part as a result of the suffragists' dedicated opposition.<ref>{{cite book|last=Marecco|first=Anne|title=The Rebel Countess|year=1967|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson}}</ref>\n\nIn 1909 Markievicz and [[Bulmer Hobson]] founded [[Fianna \u00c9ireann]], a [[para-military]] nationalist scouting organisation that instructed teenage boys in the use of firearms. At its first meeting in [[Camden Street, Dublin]], on 16 August 1909, she was almost expelled on the basis that women did not belong in a physical force movement, but Hobson supported her, and she was elected to the committee.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Townshend|first1=Charles|title=Easter 1916: The Irish Rebellion|date=2006|publisher=Penguin Books|location=London|isbn=978-0-14-190276-0|pages=21\u20132|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g6FNKxBJXMYC|accessdate=27 March 2016}}</ref> She was jailed for the first time in 1911 for speaking at an [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]] demonstration attended by 30,000 people, organised to protest against [[George V of the United Kingdom|George V]]'s visit to Ireland. During this protest Markievicz handed out leaflets, erected great masts: ''Dear land thou art not conquered yet.'', participated in stone-throwing at pictures of the King and Queen and attempted to burn the giant British flag taken from [[Leinster House]], eventually succeeding, but then seeing James McArdle imprisoned for one month for the incident, despite Markievicz testifying in court that she was responsible.<ref name=\"Ward_1983_78\">{{cite book |last1=Ward |first1=Margaret |title=Unmanageable Revolutionaries: Women and Irish Nationalism |date=1983 |publisher=Pluto Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-86104-700-0 |page=78 |ref=harv}}</ref> Her friend [[Helena Molony]] was arrested for her part in the stone-throwing and became the first woman in Ireland to be tried and imprisoned for a political act since the time of the [[Fanny Parnell#Ladies' Land League|Ladies Land League]].<ref name=\"Ward_1983_78\" />\n\nMarkievicz also joined [[James Connolly]]'s socialist [[Irish Citizen Army]] (ICA), a small volunteer force formed in response to the [[Dublin Lockout|lock-out]] of 1913, to defend the demonstrating workers from the police. Markievicz recruited volunteers to peel potatoes in a basement while she and others worked on distributing the food. As all the food was paid out of her own pocket,{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}} Markievicz was forced to take out many loans, at this time, and sold all her jewellery. That same year, with Inghinidhe na h\u00c9ireann, she ran a soup kitchen to feed poor school children.\n\nFashion advice attributed to her was: \"Dress suitably in short skirts and strong boots, leave your jewels in the bank and buy a revolver.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Sigillito|first=Gina|title=The Daughters of Maeve: 50 Irish Women Who Changed World|date=2007|publisher=Kensington Publishing Corp.|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8065-3609-5|page=87|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XfUCl5tHDNUC&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Easter Rising ==\n[[File:Countess Markievicz.jpg|thumb|left|Markievicz in uniform examining a [[Colt New Service]] Model 1909 revolver, posed c.1915]]\nIn 1913 Markievicz's husband moved back to Ukraine, and never returned to live in Ireland. However, they did correspond and he was by her side when she died in 1927. As a member of the ICA, Markievicz took part in the 1916 [[Easter Rising]]. She was deeply inspired by the founder of the [[Irish Citizen Army|ICA]], [[James Connolly]]. Markievicz designed the Citizen Army uniform and composed its anthem, based on the tune of a Polish song.<ref>{{cite book|last=Markievicz|first=Constance|title=A Battle Hymn|date=c. 1917|publisher=Irish Traditional Music Archive|url=http://www.itma.ie/digitallibrary/book/battle-hymn|accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the Rising, Markievicz fought in [[St Stephen's Green]], where on the first morning\u2014according to one account\u2014she shot a member of the (unarmed) [[Dublin Metropolitan Police]], Constable Lahiff, who subsequently died of his injuries.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Matthews|first1=Ann|title=Renegades: Irish Republican Women 1900\u20131922|date=2010|publisher=Mercier Press Ltd.|isbn=978-1-85635-684-8|pages=129\u201330|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pzYkTYi3JRgC&pg=PA129|accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Arrington |first=Lauren |url=http://irishhistoriansinbritain.org/?p=18 |title=Did Constance Markievicz Shoot the Policeman? |website=Conference of Irish Historians in Britain}}</ref>\nDistrict nurse Geraldine Fitzgerald, recorded in her diary that as she was returning from duty to the nurses' home, located at the southwest corner of the Green, she saw:\n\n{{quote|A lady in a green uniform, the same as the men were wearing (breeches, slouch hat with green feathers etc.) the feathers were the only feminine feature in her appearance, holding a revolver in one hand and a cigarette in the other, was standing on the footpath giving orders to the men. We recognized her as the Countess de Markievicz \u2013 such a specimen of womanhood. There were other women, similarly attired, inside the Park, walking about and bringing drinks of water to the men. We had only been looking out a few minutes when we saw a policeman walking down the path from Harcourt Street. He had only gone a short way when we heard a shot and then saw him fall forward on his face. The Countess ran triumphantly into the Green saying \u201cI got him\u201d and some of the rebels shook her by the hand and seemed to congratulate her.<ref>Geraldine Fitzgerald, extract from diary in Castle File no. 84 (Constance Markievicz), NA, WO 35/207</ref>}}\n\nOther accounts place her at [[City Hall, Dublin|City Hall]] when the policeman was shot, only arriving at Stephen's Green later.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Constance Markievicz: Irish Revolutionary |last=Haverty |first=Anne |author-link=Anne Haverty|year=1988 |publisher=Pandora |location=London |isbn=978-0-86358-161-8 |page=148 }}</ref> It was long thought that she was second in command to [[Michael Mallin]],{{sfnp|Ward|1983|p=112}} but in fact it was [[Christopher \"Kit\" Poole]] who held that position.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Millar|first1=Scott|title=Not for fame or for name|journal=Liberty|date=December 2013|volume=12|issue=10|page=23}}</ref> Markievicz supervised the setting-up of barricades on Easter Monday and was in the middle of the fighting all around Stephen's Green, wounding a [[British army]] sniper.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McKenna|first1=Joseph|title=Guerrilla Warfare in the Irish War of Independence, 1919\u20131921|date=2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8519-2|page=112|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BxLb0aZOFOMC&pg=PA112|accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref> Trenches were dug in the Green, sheltered by the front gate; however, after British machine gun and rifle fire from the rooftops of tall buildings on the north side of the Green including the Shelbourne Hotel, the Citizen Army troops withdrew to the [[Royal College of Surgeons in Ireland|Royal College of Surgeons]] on the west side of the Green.\n\nThe Stephen's Green garrison held out for six days, ending the engagement when the British brought them a copy of Pearse's surrender order. The British officer, Captain (later Major) de Courcy Wheeler, who accepted their surrender was married to Markievicz's first cousin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mauser pistol handed to me by Countess Markievicz when she surrendered to me at the College of Surgeons Dublin in 1916 with Commandant Mallin. H. E. de C. Wheeler. This was presented to me by General Lowe| url=http://catalogue.nli.ie/Record/vtls000652512/HierarchyTree|website=Catalogue|publisher=National Library of Ireland|accessdate=5 January 2016| date=1916}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bunbury|first1=Turtle|title=Dorothea Findlater \u2013 One Hundred Years On|url=http://www.turtlebunbury.com/interviews/interviews_misc/interviews_misc_dorotheafindlater.html|accessdate=5 January 2016|quote=Perhaps the most awkward arrest Wheeler made was Countess Markievicz, his wife\u2019s first cousin.}}</ref>\n\nThey were taken to Dublin Castle and Markievicz was transported to [[Kilmainham Gaol]]. They were jeered by the crowds as they walked through the streets of Dublin. There, she was the only one of 70 women prisoners who was put into solitary confinement. At her court martial on 4 May 1916, Markievicz pleaded not guilty to \"taking part in an armed rebellion...for the purpose of assisting the enemy,\" but pleaded guilty to having attempted \"to cause disaffection among the civil population of His Majesty\".<ref name=\"FoyBarton303\">{{cite book|last1=Foy|first1=Michael T.|last2=Barton|first2=Brian|title=The Easter Rising|date=2011|publisher=The History Press|isbn=978-0-7524-7272-0|page=303|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wUI7AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA303|accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref>  Markievicz told the court, \"I went out to fight for Ireland's freedom and it does not matter what happens to me. I did what I thought was right and I stand by it.\"<ref name=FoyBarton303 />{{sfnp|Arrington|2015|p=141}} She was sentenced to death, but the court recommended mercy \"solely and only on account of her sex\".<ref name=FoyBarton303 /> The sentence was commuted to life in prison. When told of this, she said to her captors, \"I do wish your lot had the decency to shoot me\".{{efn|In 1939, 2-Lt William Wylie KC, the prosecutor, published a dissenting account that she \"curled up completely\", \"never stopped moaning\" and cried \"I am only a woman, and you cannot shoot a woman.  You must not shoot a woman.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Richardson |first=Neil |title=According to their Lights: Stories of Irishmen in the British Army, Easter 1916 |publisher=The Collins Press |location=Cork |date=2015 |chapter=Chapter 8: Dublin University Officer Training Corps: The Defence of Trinity College Dublin |isbn=978-1-84889-214-9}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dowler|first1=Lorraine|editor1-last=Flint|editor1-first=Colin|title=The Geography of War and Peace: From Death Camps to Diplomats|date=2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-534751-7|page=144|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Za08XQfp3ZwC&pg=PA144&|accessdate=30 March 2016|chapter=Amazonian Landscapes: Gender, War, and Historical Repetition}}</ref>\n\nMarkievicz was transferred to [[Mountjoy Prison]] and then to [[HM Prison Aylesbury|Aylesbury Prison]] in England in July 1916. She was released from prison in 1917, along with others involved in the Rising, as the government in London granted a general amnesty for those who had participated in it. It was around this time that Markievicz, born into the [[Church of Ireland]], converted to [[Catholicism]].\n\n== First D\u00e1il ==\n[[File:Following the pipers! (29677821546).jpg|thumb|Election victory procession led by Markievicz in [[County Clare]] ]]\nIn 1918, she was jailed again for her part in anti-conscription activities. At the [[1918 Irish general election|1918 general election]], Markievicz was elected for the constituency of [[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick's]], beating her opponent [[William Field (Irish politician)|William Field]] with 66% of the vote, as one of 73 [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MPs]]. The results were called on 28 December 1918.<ref name=dec28>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishlabourhistorysociety.com/pdf/Markievicz.pdf|title=Countess Markievicz\u2014'The Rebel Countess'|website=Irish Labour History Society|access-date=17 December 2017}}</ref> This made her the first woman elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom House of Commons]]. However, in line with Sinn F\u00e9in [[abstentionism|abstentionist]] policy, she did not take her seat in the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Archives \u2013 The First Women MPs |website=UK Parliament |url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/parliamentary-archives/explore-guides-to-documentary-archive-/archives-highlights/archives-the-suffragettes/archives-the-first-women-in-parliament-1919-1945 |accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nMarkievicz was in [[Holloway (HM Prison)|Holloway prison]], when her colleagues assembled in Dublin at the first meeting of the [[First D\u00e1il]], the Parliament of the revolutionary [[Irish Republic]]. When her name was called, she was described, like many of those elected, as being \"imprisoned by the foreign enemy\" (''f\u00e9 ghlas ag Gallaibh'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishresistancebooks.com/internment/intern6.htm|title=Internment \u2013 Women Internees 1916\u20131973|first=John |last=McGuffin|year=1973\n|accessdate=22 March 2009}}</ref> She was re-elected to the [[Second D\u00e1il]] in the [[1921 Irish elections|elections of 1921]].<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?id=994|title=Countess Constance de Markievicz|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=22 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nMarkievicz served as [[Minister for Labour (Ireland)|Minister for Labour]] from April 1919 to January 1922, in the [[Government of the 1st D\u00e1il#Second Ministry|Second Ministry]] and the [[Government of the 2nd D\u00e1il#Third Ministry|Third Ministry]] of the D\u00e1il. Holding cabinet rank from April to August 1919, she became both the first Irish female [[Cabinet (government)|Cabinet Minister]] and at the same time, only the second female government minister in Europe.{{efn|name=firstm}}{{sfnp|Ward|1983|p=137}} She was the only female cabinet minister in [[History of Ireland|Irish history]] until 1979 when [[M\u00e1ire Geoghegan-Quinn]] was appointed to the cabinet post of [[Minister for Community, Rural and Gaeltacht Affairs|Minister for the Gaeltacht]] for Fianna F\u00e1il.\n\n== Civil War and Fianna F\u00e1il ==\n[[File:Constance Markiewicz in st stephens green.JPG|thumb|upright|The bust of Constance Markievicz in [[St Stephen's Green]] in Dublin.]]\nMarkievicz left government in January 1922 along with [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] and others in opposition to the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]]. She fought actively for the [[Irish republicanism|Republican]] cause in the [[Irish Civil War]], including the occupation of Moran's Hotel in Dublin. After the War she toured the United States. She was not elected in the [[1922 Irish general election]] but was returned in the [[1923 Irish general election|1923 general election]] for the [[Dublin South (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin South]] constituency. In common with other [[Irish republicanism|Republican]] candidates, she did not take her D\u00e1il seat. She was arrested again in November 1923. In prison, she went on hunger strike, and within a month, she and other prisoners were released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dib.cambridge.org/viewReadPage.do?articleId=a5452|last=Pa\u0161eta|first=Senia|title=Markievicz, Constance Georgine|website=Dictionary of Irish Biography|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe left Sinn Fein and joined the new [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] party on its foundation in 1926, chairing the inaugural meeting of the new party in La Scala Theatre. In the [[June 1927 Irish general election|June 1927 general election]], she was re-elected to the [[5th D\u00e1il]] as a candidate for Fianna F\u00e1il, which was pledged to return to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]], but died only five weeks later, before she could take her seat.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Co%EF%BB%BFnstance-Georgina-de-Markievicz.D.1919-01-21/|title=Constance Georgina de Markievicz |website=Houses of the Oireachtas |accessdate=23 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123131545/https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Co%EF%BB%BFnstance-Georgina-de-Markievicz.D.1919-01-21/ |archive-date=23 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Her fellow Fianna F\u00e1il TDs signed the controversial [[Oath of Allegiance (Ireland)|Oath of Allegiance]] and took their seats in the D\u00e1il on 12 August 1927, less than a month after her death.<ref>[https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1927-08-12/2/ New Deputies take their seats \u2013 D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann debate \u2013 Friday, 12 Aug 1927]</ref> The party leader \u00c9amon de Valera described the Oath as \"an empty political formula\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/ashorthistory/archive/intro236.shtml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820044651/http://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/ashorthistory/archive/intro236.shtml |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 August 2010 |title=BBC's Short History of Ireland |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=21 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nMarkievicz died at the age of 59 on 15 July 1927, of complications related to [[appendicitis]]. She had given away the last of her wealth, and died in a public ward \"among the poor where she wanted to be\".<ref name=Depuis>{{cite book|last=Depuis|first=Nicola|title=Mn\u00e1 Na H\u00c9ireann: Women who Shaped Ireland|date=2009|publisher=Mercier Press Ltd|location=Cork|isbn=978-1-85635-645-9|page=171|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=heeon5xC5KwC&pg=PA171#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Levenson|first1=Leah|last2=Natterstad|first2=Jerry H.|title=Hanna Sheehy-Skeffington: Irish Feminist|date=1989|publisher=Syracuse University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8156-2480-6|page=452|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MCJO7AX9tjsC&pg=PA152#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref> One of the doctors attending her was her revolutionary colleague, [[Kathleen Lynn]].<ref name=II1927>{{cite news|title=Death of Madame Marcievicz|newspaper=Irish Independent|date=15 July 1927}}</ref> Also at her bedside were Casimir and Stanislas Markievicz, \u00c9amon de Valera and [[Hanna Sheehy-Skeffington]].<ref name=II1927 /> Refused a state funeral by the [[Irish Free State|Free State]] government, she was buried at [[Glasnevin Cemetery]], Dublin, and de Valera gave the funeral oration.<ref name=Depuis /><ref>{{cite news|title=The Late Madame Marcievicz: An Impressive Funeral|newspaper=Irish Independent|date=18 July 1927}}</ref>\n\n[[Se\u00e1n O'Casey]] said of her: \"One thing she had in abundance\u2014physical courage; with that she was clothed as with a garment.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Ratcliffe|first=Susan|title=People on People: The Oxford Dictionary of Biographical Quotations|date=2001|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-866261-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/peopleonpeopleox0000unse/page/235 235]|url=https://archive.org/details/peopleonpeopleox0000unse/page/235}}</ref>\n[[File:Constance Markievicz 1.jpg|thumb|A Dublin City Council 1916 Commemorative plaque, unveiled on 15 July 2019, to commemorate Constance Markievicz and the house she lived in from 1912\u20131916]]\n\n== Tributes ==\nIn 2018 a portrait of Markievicz was donated by the Irish government to the British House of Commons to commemorate the [[Representation of the People Act 1918|1918 Representation of the People Act]], in which, some women were allowed the right to vote for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/press-centre/press-releases/20180719-picture-of-constance-markievicz-first-woman-elected-to-house-of-commons-gifted-to-uk-by-ceann-comhairle|title=Picture of Constance Markievicz, first woman elected to House of Commons, gifted to UK by Ceann Comhairle \u2013 19 Jul 2018, 11.20 \u2013 Houses of the Oireachtas|last=Oireachtas|first=Houses of the|date=2018-07-19|website=www.oireachtas.ie|language=en-ie|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 a Dublin City Council Commemorative Plaque was unveiled at Markievicz\u2019s former home in Rathmines, which is Surrey House on Leinster Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dublingazette.com/news/news-city-edition/markievicz-plaque-89230/ |title=Countess Markievicz is honoured with a plaque at Rathmines home |publisher=Dublingazette.com |date= |accessdate=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Portal|Politics}}\n{{Notes}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|first=Se\u00e1n|last= O'Faolain|title=Constance Markievicz|date=1934}}\n* {{cite book|first=Damian|last= Lawlor|title=Na Fianna \u00c9ireann and the Irish Revolution- 1909\u20131923|date=2009}}\n* {{cite book|first=Anne|last= Marreco|author-link=Anne Wignall|title=The Rebel Countess: The Life and Times of Constance Markievicz|date=1967}}\n* {{cite book|first=Diana|last= Norman|title=Terrible Beauty: A Life of Constance Markievicz, 1868\u20131927|date=1987}}\n* {{cite book|first=Anne|last= Haverty|author-link=Anne Haverty|title=Constance Markievicz: Irish Revolutionary|date=1993}}\n* {{cite book|first=Joe|last= McGowan|title=Constance Markievicz: The People's Countess|date=2003}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacqueline|last= Van Voris|title=Constance de Markievicz: In The Cause of Ireland|date=1967}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Constance Markiewicz|Constance Markievicz}}\n* [http://www.sligoheritage.com/archMark.htm Article on Constance Markievicz]\n* [https://digital.library.villanova.edu/Item/vudl:526517 \u2018Women, ideals and the nation\u2019] speech available from the [https://digital.library.villanova.edu/ Digital Library@Villanova University]\n* [http://www.ucc.ie/celt/published/E900003-001/ Her speeches in the Treaty Debates]\n* [http://our-ireland.com/the-irish-rebel-countess-markievicz/ Life As A Rebel & Co-Founder of The Irish Citizen's Army]\n* [http://www.easter1916.ie/index.php/people/a-z/countess-constance-markievicz/ Countess Markievicz and Easter 1916]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[William Field (Irish politician)|William Field]]<br /><small>([[Irish Parliamentary Party]])</small>}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick's]]\n       |years  = 1918\u20131922}}\n{{s-non|reason = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = {{nowrap|[[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Dublin St Patrick's (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin St Patrick's]]}}\n       |years  = 1918\u20131921}}\n{{s-non|reason = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] Teachta D\u00e1la for [[Dublin South (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin South]]\n       |years  = 1921\u20131922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Myles Keogh (Irish politician)|Myles Keogh]]<br /><small>([[Independent (politician)|Independent]])</small>}}\n{{s-bef|before = New seat in constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] Teachta D\u00e1la for Dublin South\n       |years  = 1923\u20131927}}\n{{s-aft|after  = Herself|as = a Fianna F\u00e1il TD}}\n{{s-bef|before =  Herself|as = a Sinn F\u00e9in TD}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] Teachta D\u00e1la for Dublin South\n       |years  = June\u2013July 1927}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Thomas Hennessy]]<br /><small>([[Cumann na nGaedheal]])</small>}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Labour (Ireland)|Minister for Labour]]\n       |years  = 1919\u20131922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Joseph McGrath (Irish politician)|Joseph McGrath]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{2nd Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{3rd Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{Easter Rising}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Markievicz, Constance}}\n[[Category:1868 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]\n[[Category:British female MPs]]\n[[Category:British suffragists]]\n[[Category:Burials at Glasnevin Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Catholic socialists]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism from Anglicanism]]\n[[Category:Cumann na mBan members]]\n[[Category:Daughters of baronets]]\n[[Category:Early Sinn F\u00e9in TDs]]\n[[Category:Fianna F\u00e1il TDs]]\n[[Category:Gore family (Anglo-Irish aristocracy)|Constance]]\n[[Category:Irish Citizen Army members]]\n[[Category:Irish revolutionaries]]\n[[Category:Members of the 1st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 4th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 5th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Dublin constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:People of the Easter Rising]]\n[[Category:People of the Irish Civil War (Anti-Treaty side)]]\n[[Category:Polish nobility]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Sligo]]\n[[Category:Socialist feminists]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:Women Teachta\u00ed D\u00e1la]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Women in war 1900\u20131945]]\n[[Category:Women in war in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Women of the Victorian era]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: Sinn Fein \u2192 Sinn F\u00e9in, \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constance_Markievicz"}
{"title_page": "Andorian", "text_new": "{{For|adjectives related to the nation of Andorra|Andorran (disambiguation){{!}}Andorran}}\n{{short description|Extraterrestrial from Star Trek}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox fictional race\n| name               = Andorians\n| other_names        = [[List of Star Trek races#Aenar|Aenar]] ''(sub-species)''\n| image              = ProvingGround1.jpg\n| caption            = Commander Shran and crew from the 2004 ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]'' episode \"[[Proving Ground (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Proving Ground]]\".\n| series             = [[Star Trek]]\n| home_world         = Andoria\n| affiliation        = [[United Federation of Planets]], [[#Empire|Andorian Empire]]\n}}\n\n'''Andorians''' are a fictional race of [[humanoid]] [[Extraterrestrial life|extraterrestrials]] in the American [[science fiction]] franchise ''[[Star Trek]]''. They were created by writer [[D. C. Fontana]]. Within the ''Star Trek'' narrative, they are native to the blue icy Class M planet Andoria (also called Andor<ref name=ProphetCards>The home planet was first referred to as \"Andoria\" in Act 1 of \"[[Prophet Motive]]\", and as \"Andor\" in Act 3 of \"[[In the Cards]]\".</ref>). Distinctive traits of Andorians include their blue skin, a pair of [[Skull|cranial]] [[antenna (biology)|antenna]]e, and white hair.<ref name=\"com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.startrek.com/database_article/andoria |title=Andoria |work=Star Trek Database |publisher=StarTrek.com |accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nAndorians first appeared in the 1968 ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series]]'' episode \"[[Journey to Babel]]\", and have been seen or mentioned in episodes of subsequent series in the ''Star Trek'' franchise. They were indicated to be a vital, important member of the [[United Federation of Planets]] in the 1997 ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'' episode \"[[In the Cards]]\", but did not gain considerable exposure until the 2001\u20132005 series ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]'', on which they were used as recurring characters, most notably in the person of [[List of minor recurring characters in Star Trek: Enterprise#Thy'lek Shran|Thy'lek Shran]], a starship commander who maintained a sometimes adversarial and begrudging friendship with ''Enterprise'' Captain [[Jonathan Archer]]. The series revealed more about Andorian ships, the home world Andoria, and the culture and history of Andorians and their subspecies, the Aenar. The 2004 episode \"[[Zero Hour (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Zero Hour]]\" established that Andorians were one of the four founding members of the United Federation of Planets.<ref name=ZeroHour>{{cite episode|series=[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]|title=[[Zero Hour (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Zero Hour]]|network=[[UPN]]|airdate=May 26, 2004|season=3|number=24}}</ref>\n\n== Storyline ==\n[[File:JourneyBabel.jpg|thumb|left|Thelev, an [[Orion (Star Trek)|Orion]] assassin disguised as an Andorian, from the 1967 [[Star Trek: The Original Series|original series]] episode \"[[Journey to Babel]]\".]]\nAndorians appeared in four episodes of The Original Series, but there was very little back story on the Andorians until Enterprise.<ref name=StarshipsCollection37>Fred Dekker, Star Trek: The Official Starships Collection, issue 37, p. 11</ref> Historically, the Andorians were rivals with the [[Vulcan (Star Trek)|Vulcans]]. In the episode \"The Andorian Incident\", the Andorian Imperial Guard appeared on a Vulcan [[monastery]] world [[The Andorian Incident|P'Jem]] to search for a spy station, destroying property in the process. Archer discovered the spy station and informed the Andorians, leading to Shran (an Andorian) to become trusting of Archer. The tensions between Andor and Vulcan were gradually resolved with human aid. Also in this episode, Andorians begin to refer to humans using the [[pejorative]] \"pink-skin.\"\n\nIn the third season of Enterprise, Shran offers Archer assistance in retrieving a prototype of the Xindi weapon, only to be betrayed by Shran when he takes the weapon. Archer believed Shran would use the weapon against the Vulcans, to remotely set the detonation sequence. Shran removed the weapon from his ship before it exploded. In the season 3 finale, Shran helped Archer fight the Xindi reptilians who were bringing the final weapon to Earth.\n\nIn the episode \"United\", an Andorian dies from a phaser wound, leading Shran to challenge a Tellarite to a the Ushaan. In Andorian tradition, the Ushaan is a duel to the death, which is fought with hand-held ice-cutting blades called Ushaan-Tor, as mentioned in the second scene of Act 3. The Ushaan Right of Substitution allows combatants to choose another combatant to fight in their place. The Ushaan is settled when a combatant is rendered defenseless. Archer takes the Tellarite's place, and wins the duel when he cuts off Shran's antenna.<ref name=United/>\n\n== Appearance ==\nAndorians have blue blood, blue skin, white hair, and antennae on the crown of the skull. By the time of the 2001 \u2013 2005 TV series ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]'', the antennae were depicted as protruding from the forehead, and capable of movement, used for [[gesture|gesturing]] and [[vestibular system|balancing]]. If cut off, an antenna will grow back after nine months, though the time can be reduced by half with electrical stimulation and brisk cranial massage.<ref name=United>{{cite episode|title=[[United (Star Trek: Enterprise)|United]]|series=Star Trek: Enterprise|airdate=February 4, 2005|network=UPN|season=4|number=13}}</ref>\n\nThe [[List of Star Trek races#Aenar|Aenar]] are a more reclusive, blue-white-skinned subspecies of Androians. They were considered a myth until contact was remade in the episode \"[[The Aenar]]\", during the fourth season of Enterprise. The Aenar are blind, but exhibit [[telepathy|telepathic]] and [[telemetry|telemetric]] abilities. Aenar appear to use their antennae as telepathic receptors.<ref name=TheAenar>{{cite episode|title=[[The Aenar]]|series=Star Trek: Enterprise|season=4|number=14|network=UPN|airdate=February 11, 2005}}</ref>\n\n== Planet ==\nAndoria is an icy moon orbiting a ringed [[gas giant]]. It has also been referred to as Andor.<ref name=ProphetCards/> In a DVD bonus feature for the 4th season of ''Enterprise'', episode writers [[Judith Reeves-Stevens|Judith]] and [[Garfield Reeves-Stevens]] stated that Andor was the gas giant, Andoria the moon, and that this was a conscious effort to address the discrepancy. Most of its cities are built underground to take advantage of [[Geothermal gradient|geothermal]] warmth. Temperatures have been known to reach \u221228 \u00b0[[Celsius|C]] in the summer. Andoria has at least one moon or neighboring planet. Andorians share their homeworld with an obscure telepathic subspecies, [[List of Star Trek races#Aenar|Aenar]], which have either light blue or white skin.<ref name=TheAenar/>\n\nThe non-canonical ''Star Trek Star Charts'' (2002) cites Andor as the seventh planet in orbit around the star [[Procyon]] (Alpha Canis Minoris) in the [[Galactic quadrant#Alpha Quadrant|Beta quadrant]],<ref>Geoffrey Mandel, ''Star Trek Star Charts: The Complete Atlas of Star Trek'' (NY: Pocket Books, 2002), 52.</ref> but previous material has Andor as the eighth planet of the orange dwarf [[Epsilon Indi]] in the [[Galactic quadrant#Alpha Quadrant|Alpha quadrant]].<ref>Eileen Palestine, ed., ''Star Fleet Medical Reference Manual'' (NY: Ballantine Books, 1977), 58.</ref><ref name=\"Shane Johnson 1989\">Shane Johnson, ''The Worlds of the Federation'' (NY: Pocket Books, 1989), 22.</ref> Andor is near [[Betazoid#Betazed|Betazed]], [[Earth]], [[Tellarite|Tellar]], and [[Vulcan (Star Trek)|Vulcan]].\n\n== Noncanonical information ==\n{{more citations needed section|date=October 2008}}\nA 1970s technical fiction book, ''The Starfleet Medical Reference Manual'', held that Andorians were the only known semi-insectoid race in Federation territory, with a limited [[exoskeleton]] and antennae used for both quadriscopic vision reception and focused hearing.<ref>Eileen Palestine, ed., ''Star Fleet Medical Reference Manual'' (NY: Ballantine Books, 1977).</ref> These points were repeated in the 1980s book ''Worlds of the Federation''.<ref name=\"Shane Johnson 1989\"/> Fully insectoid races depicted or referred to onscreen include the unseen Jarada in the ''Next Generation'' episode \"[[The Big Goodbye]]\", and the [[Xindi (Star Trek)#Xindi-Insectoids|Xindi]], which were introduced in ''Star Trek: Enterprise''{{'}}s third season.\n\nIn the ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine relaunch|Deep Space Nine]]'' relaunch novels, four-person Andorian marriages were extrapolated into four sexes (''thaan'', ''chen'', ''shen'', and ''zhen'').<ref>S. D. Perry, ''Star Trek: Deep Space Nine \u2013 Unity'' (NY: Pocket Books, 2003).</ref> A recurring plot point in the post-TV series novels is that the rarity of compatible Andorian foursomes produced extremely low reproduction rates which, in tandem with genetic weaknesses, led to the species' near extinction.\n\nSimilarly, the [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] comic book ''[[Star Trek: Starfleet Academy (comics)|Star Trek: Starfleet Academy]]'' refers to complex yet flexible marital structures, involving one or more fathers, and describes Andorians as passionate, with a violent history.<ref>''Star Trek: Starfleet Academy'', issue #13, ''Parents' Day'' (Marvel/Paramount Comics, 1997).</ref>\n\nIn the Pocket Books continuity, specifically the 2010 novel, ''Star Trek: Typhon Pact \u2013 Paths of Disharmony'' by [[Dayton Ward]], the Andorian Empire withdraws from the Federation in 2382.<ref>Dayton Ward, ''Star Trek: Typhon Pact \u2013 Paths of Disharmony'' (NY: Pocket Books, 2010).</ref> However, the Andorian government still maintains diplomatic relations with the Federation, and Andorian officers are allowed to remain in [[Starfleet]] if they so choose. Despite Andor's withdrawal, a sizable percentage of the population \u2013 represented in the Andorian government by the \"New Progressive Party\", as opposed to the secessionist \"Visionist Party\" \u2013 favored continuing membership in the Federation, opening the possibility of a later reunification. In a subsequent novel, Dayton Ward's ''Star Trek: The Fall \u2013 Peaceable Kingdoms'', Andor does rejoin the Federation.<ref>Dayton Ward, ''Star Trek: The Fall \u2013 Peaceable Kingdoms'' (NY: Pocket Books, 2013).</ref>\n\nIn the [[Free-to-play]] online role-playing game ''[[Star Trek Online]]'', which takes place in 2409, the Andorians are still ordinary members of the Federation.\n\nIn the [[Fan film]] episodic series ''[[Starship Exeter]]'', the communications officer on the bridge is an Andorian Lieutenant named B'fuselek.  In this series it is explained that Andorians' antennae give the Andorians the ability to detect nearby fluctuations in gravity, and know their position in relation to these gravity differences. Andorians and Vulcans also have a history of feuding over many things.\n\n==Appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|+ ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series]]''\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! '''#''' || '''Episode''' || '''Appearance'''\n|-\n| 210     || \"[[Journey to Babel]]\" || Andorian Ambassador, plus an Orion spy, posing as the Ambassador's aide, who frames Sarek for murder \n|-\n| 216     || \"[[The Gamesters of Triskelion]]\" || One of the slaves of Triskelion\n|-\n| 314     || \"[[Whom Gods Destroy (Star Trek: The Original Series)|Whom Gods Destroy]]\" || One of the mental patients was Andorian\n|-\n| 318     || \"[[The Lights of Zetar]]\" || Two Andorian scholars were present at Memory Alpha at the time of its destruction\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|+ ''[[Star Trek: The Animated Series]]''\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! '''#''' || '''Episode''' || '''Appearance'''\n|-\n| 102     || \"[[Yesteryear (Star Trek: The Animated Series)|Yesteryear]]\" || [[Spock]] replaced by Andorian first officer, Thelin, in alternate timeline\n|-\n| 112     || \"[[The Time Trap]]\" || Andorian on the Elysian Council, plus a member of his old crew in background\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|+ ''Star Trek: Movies''\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! '''Episode''' || '''Appearance'''\n|-\n| ''[[Star Trek: The Motion Picture]]'' || Three ambassadors in crowd at Starfleet Headquarters; two crew on ''Enterprise'' Rec Deck\n|-\n| ''[[Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home]]'' || Two members of Starfleet on the Federation Council\n|-\n| ''[[Star Trek V: The Final Frontier]]'' || Script suggests one \"face of God\" was Andorian; see bonus scenes of two-disk DVD\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|+ ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]''\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! '''#''' || '''Episode''' || '''Appearance'''\n|-\n| 316     || \"[[The Offspring (Star Trek: The Next Generation)|The Offspring]]\" || A young Andorian female is shown as one possible choice of appearance for Data's new child, Lal.\n|-\n| 319    || \"[[Captain's Holiday]]\" || Andorian tourist on Risa\n|-\n| 508    || \"[[Unification (Star Trek: The Next Generation)|Unification]]\" || An alien pianist plays \"Andorian blues\" for Riker\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|+ ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]''\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! '''#''' || '''Episode''' || '''Appearance'''\n|-\n| 107 || \"[[The Andorian Incident]]\" || Thy'lek Shran and three more Andorian Imperial Guard commandos\n|-\n| 114 || \"[[Shadows of P'Jem]]\" || More Andorian Imperial Guard commandos\n|-\n|-\n| 215 || \"[[Cease Fire (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Cease Fire]]\" || Numerous Andorian Imperial Guard soldiers; first appearance of Andorian starships\n|-\n| 313 || \"[[Proving Ground (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Proving Ground]]\" || Andorian Imperial Guard starship and crew; Andorian general\n|-\n| 324 || \"[[Zero Hour (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Zero Hour]]\" || Commander Shran, Andorian Imperial Guard starship\n|-\n| 409 || \"[[Kir'Shara]]\" || Numerous Andorian Imperial Guard starships\n|-\n| 412 || \"[[Babel One]]\" || Survivors of the wreck of the ''Kumari''\n|-\n| 413 || \"[[United (Star Trek: Enterprise)|United]]\" || Survivors of the wreck of the ''Kumari''\n|-\n| 414 || \"[[The Aenar]]\" || Commander Shran, several members of the Aenar subspecies\n|-\n| 418 || \"[[In a Mirror, Darkly]]\" || Crewman aboard the I.S.S. ''Enterprise''\n|-\n| 419 || \"[[In a Mirror, Darkly]]  (Part II)\" || Crewman aboard the I.S.S. ''Avenger''\n|-\n| 420 || \"[[Demons (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Demons]]\" || Andorian delegates at Coalition of Planets conference\n|-\n| 421 || \"[[Terra Prime]]\" || Andorian Ambassador, plus delegates at Coalition of Planets conference\n|-\n| 422 || \"[[These Are the Voyages...]]\" || Holographic representations of Shran and daughter circa 2161\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|+ ''[[Star Trek: Discovery]]''\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! '''#''' || '''Episode''' || '''Appearance'''\n|-\n| 11      || \"[[The Wolf Inside (Star Trek: Discovery)|The Wolf Inside]]\" || One of the leaders of the resistance coalition against Terran Empire in a mirror parallel universe\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Memory Alpha}}\n{{Memory Alpha|Andor}}\n* [http://andorfiles.blogspot.com/2000/01/tos-rogues-gallery.html A Rogues' Gallery of Andorians] \u2013 a series of blog postings listing the appearances of Andorian characters across all ''Star Trek'' media\n\n{{Star Trek}}\n\n[[Category:Star Trek species]]\n[[Category:Galactic empires]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1967]]\n\n[[cs:Rasy ve Star Treku#Andorian\u00e9]]\n[[de:V\u00f6lker und Gruppierungen im Star-Trek-Universum#Andorianer]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|adjectives related to the nation of Andorra|Andorran (disambiguation){{!}}Andorran}}\n{{short description|Extraterrestrial from Star Trek}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox fictional race\n| name               = Andorians\n| other_names        = [[List of Star Trek races#Aenar|Aenar]] ''(sub-species)''\n| image              = ProvingGround1.jpg\n| caption            = Commander Shran and crew from the 2004 ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]'' episode \"[[Proving Ground (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Proving Ground]]\".\n| series             = [[Star Trek]]\n| home_world         = Andoria\n| affiliation        = [[United Federation of Planets]], [[#Empire|Andorian Empire]]\n}}\n\n'''Andorians''' are a fictional race of [[humanoid]] [[Extraterrestrial life|extraterrestrials]] in the American [[science fiction]] franchise ''[[Star Trek]]''. They were created by writer [[D. C. Fontana]]. Within the ''Star Trek'' narrative, they are native to the blue icy Class M planet Andoria (also called Andor<ref name=ProphetCards>The home planet was first referred to as \"Andoria\" in Act 1 of \"[[Prophet Motive]]\", and as \"Andor\" in Act 3 of \"[[In the Cards]]\".</ref>). Distinctive traits of Andorians include their blue skin, a pair of [[Skull|cranial]] [[antenna (biology)|antenna]]e, and white hair.<ref name=\"com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.startrek.com/database_article/andoria |title=Andoria |work=Star Trek Database |publisher=StarTrek.com |accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nAndorians first appeared in the 1968 ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series]]'' episode \"[[Journey to Babel]]\", and have been seen or mentioned in episodes of subsequent series in the ''Star Trek'' franchise. They were indicated to be a vital, important member of the [[United Federation of Planets]] in the 1997 ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'' episode \"[[In the Cards]]\", but did not gain considerable exposure until the 2001\u20132005 series ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]'', on which they were used as recurring characters, most notably in the person of [[List of minor recurring characters in Star Trek: Enterprise#Thy'lek Shran|Thy'lek Shran]], a starship commander who maintained a sometimes adversarial and begrudging friendship with ''Enterprise'' Captain [[Jonathan Archer]]. The series revealed more about Andorian ships, the home world Andoria, and the culture and history of Andorians and their subspecies, the Aenar. The 2004 episode \"[[Zero Hour (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Zero Hour]]\" established that Andorians were one of the four founding members of the United Federation of Planets.<ref name=ZeroHour>{{cite episode|series=[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]|title=[[Zero Hour (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Zero Hour]]|network=[[UPN]]|airdate=May 26, 2004|season=3|number=24}}</ref>\n\n== Storyline ==\n[[File:JourneyBabel.jpg|thumb|left|Thelev, an [[Orion (Star Trek)|Orion]] assassin disguised as an Andorian, from the 1967 [[Star Trek: The Original Series|original series]] episode \"[[Journey to Babel]]\".]]\nAndorians appeared in four episodes of The Original Series, but there was very little back story on the Andorians until Enterprise. <ref name=StarshipsCollection37>Fred Dekker, Star Trek: The Official Starships Collection, issue 37, p. 11</ref>. Historically, the Andorians were rivals with the [[Vulcan (Star Trek)|Vulcans]]. In the episode \"The Andorian Incident\", the Andorian Imperial Guard appeared on a Vulcan [[monastery]] world [[The Andorian Incident|P'Jem]] to search for a spy station, destroying property in the process. Archer discovered the spy station and informed the Andorians, leading to Shran (an Andorian) to become trusting of Archer. The tensions between Andor and Vulcan were gradually resolved with human aid. Also in this episode, Andorians begin to refer to humans using the [[pejorative]] \"pink-skin.\"\n\nIn the third season of Enterprise, Shran offers Archer assistance in retrieving a prototype of the Xindi weapon, only to be betrayed by Shran when he takes the weapon. Archer believed Shran would use the weapon against the Vulcans, to remotely set the detonation sequence. Shran removed the weapon from his ship before it exploded. In the season 3 finale, Shran helped Archer fight the Xindi reptilians who were bringing the final weapon to Earth.\n\nIn the episode \"United\", an Andorian dies from a phaser wound, leading Shran to challenge a Tellarite to a the Ushaan. In Andorian tradition, the Ushaan is a duel to the death, which is fought with hand-held ice-cutting blades called Ushaan-Tor, as mentioned in the second scene of Act 3. The Ushaan Right of Substitution allows combatants to choose another combatant to fight in their place. The Ushaan is settled when a combatant is rendered defenseless. Archer takes the Tellarite's place, and wins the duel when he cuts off Shran's antenna.<ref name=United/>\n\n== Appearance ==\nAndorians have blue blood, blue skin, white hair, and antennae on the crown of the skull. By the time of the 2001 \u2013 2005 TV series ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]'', the antennae were depicted as protruding from the forehead, and capable of movement, used for [[gesture|gesturing]] and [[vestibular system|balancing]]. If cut off, an antenna will grow back after nine months, though the time can be reduced by half with electrical stimulation and brisk cranial massage.<ref name=United>{{cite episode|title=[[United (Star Trek: Enterprise)|United]]|series=Star Trek: Enterprise|airdate=February 4, 2005|network=UPN|season=4|number=13}}</ref>\n\nThe [[List of Star Trek races#Aenar|Aenar]] are a more reclusive, blue-white-skinned subspecies of Androians. They were considered a myth until contact was remade in the episode \"[[The Aenar]]\", during the fourth season of Enterprise. The Aenar are blind, but exhibit [[telepathy|telepathic]] and [[telemetry|telemetric]] abilities. Aenar appear to use their antennae as telepathic receptors.<ref name=TheAenar>{{cite episode|title=[[The Aenar]]|series=Star Trek: Enterprise|season=4|number=14|network=UPN|airdate=February 11, 2005}}</ref>\n\n== Planet ==\nAndoria is an icy moon orbiting a ringed [[gas giant]]. It has also been referred to as Andor.<ref name=ProphetCards/> In a DVD bonus feature for the 4th season of ''Enterprise'', episode writers [[Judith Reeves-Stevens|Judith]] and [[Garfield Reeves-Stevens]] stated that Andor was the gas giant, Andoria the moon, and that this was a conscious effort to address the discrepancy. Most of its cities are built underground to take advantage of [[Geothermal gradient|geothermal]] warmth. Temperatures have been known to reach \u221228 \u00b0[[Celsius|C]] in the summer. Andoria has at least one moon or neighboring planet. Andorians share their homeworld with an obscure telepathic subspecies, [[List of Star Trek races#Aenar|Aenar]], which have either light blue or white skin.<ref name=TheAenar/>\n\nThe non-canonical ''Star Trek Star Charts'' (2002) cites Andor as the seventh planet in orbit around the star [[Procyon]] (Alpha Canis Minoris) in the [[Galactic quadrant#Alpha Quadrant|Beta quadrant]],<ref>Geoffrey Mandel, ''Star Trek Star Charts: The Complete Atlas of Star Trek'' (NY: Pocket Books, 2002), 52.</ref> but previous material has Andor as the eighth planet of the orange dwarf [[Epsilon Indi]] in the [[Galactic quadrant#Alpha Quadrant|Alpha quadrant]].<ref>Eileen Palestine, ed., ''Star Fleet Medical Reference Manual'' (NY: Ballantine Books, 1977), 58.</ref><ref name=\"Shane Johnson 1989\">Shane Johnson, ''The Worlds of the Federation'' (NY: Pocket Books, 1989), 22.</ref> Andor is near [[Betazoid#Betazed|Betazed]], [[Earth]], [[Tellarite|Tellar]], and [[Vulcan (Star Trek)|Vulcan]].\n\n== Noncanonical information ==\n{{more citations needed section|date=October 2008}}\nA 1970s technical fiction book, ''The Starfleet Medical Reference Manual'', held that Andorians were the only known semi-insectoid race in Federation territory, with a limited [[exoskeleton]] and antennae used for both quadriscopic vision reception and focused hearing.<ref>Eileen Palestine, ed., ''Star Fleet Medical Reference Manual'' (NY: Ballantine Books, 1977).</ref> These points were repeated in the 1980s book ''Worlds of the Federation''.<ref name=\"Shane Johnson 1989\"/> Fully insectoid races depicted or referred to onscreen include the unseen Jarada in the ''Next Generation'' episode \"[[The Big Goodbye]]\", and the [[Xindi (Star Trek)#Xindi-Insectoids|Xindi]], which were introduced in ''Star Trek: Enterprise''{{'}}s third season.\n\nIn the ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine relaunch|Deep Space Nine]]'' relaunch novels, four-person Andorian marriages were extrapolated into four sexes (''thaan'', ''chen'', ''shen'', and ''zhen'').<ref>S. D. Perry, ''Star Trek: Deep Space Nine \u2013 Unity'' (NY: Pocket Books, 2003).</ref> A recurring plot point in the post-TV series novels is that the rarity of compatible Andorian foursomes produced extremely low reproduction rates which, in tandem with genetic weaknesses, led to the species' near extinction.\n\nSimilarly, the [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] comic book ''[[Star Trek: Starfleet Academy (comics)|Star Trek: Starfleet Academy]]'' refers to complex yet flexible marital structures, involving one or more fathers, and describes Andorians as passionate, with a violent history.<ref>''Star Trek: Starfleet Academy'', issue #13, ''Parents' Day'' (Marvel/Paramount Comics, 1997).</ref>\n\nIn the Pocket Books continuity, specifically the 2010 novel, ''Star Trek: Typhon Pact \u2013 Paths of Disharmony'' by [[Dayton Ward]], the Andorian Empire withdraws from the Federation in 2382.<ref>Dayton Ward, ''Star Trek: Typhon Pact \u2013 Paths of Disharmony'' (NY: Pocket Books, 2010).</ref> However, the Andorian government still maintains diplomatic relations with the Federation, and Andorian officers are allowed to remain in [[Starfleet]] if they so choose. Despite Andor's withdrawal, a sizable percentage of the population \u2013 represented in the Andorian government by the \"New Progressive Party\", as opposed to the secessionist \"Visionist Party\" \u2013 favored continuing membership in the Federation, opening the possibility of a later reunification. In a subsequent novel, Dayton Ward's ''Star Trek: The Fall \u2013 Peaceable Kingdoms'', Andor does rejoin the Federation.<ref>Dayton Ward, ''Star Trek: The Fall \u2013 Peaceable Kingdoms'' (NY: Pocket Books, 2013).</ref>\n\nIn the [[Free-to-play]] online role-playing game ''[[Star Trek Online]]'', which takes place in 2409, the Andorians are still ordinary members of the Federation.\n\nIn the [[Fan film]] episodic series ''[[Starship Exeter]]'', the communications officer on the bridge is an Andorian Lieutenant named B'fuselek.  In this series it is explained that Andorians' antennae give the Andorians the ability to detect nearby fluctuations in gravity, and know their position in relation to these gravity differences. Andorians and Vulcans also have a history of feuding over many things.\n\n==Appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|+ ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series]]''\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! '''#''' || '''Episode''' || '''Appearance'''\n|-\n| 210     || \"[[Journey to Babel]]\" || Andorian Ambassador, plus an Orion spy, posing as the Ambassador's aide, who frames Sarek for murder \n|-\n| 216     || \"[[The Gamesters of Triskelion]]\" || One of the slaves of Triskelion\n|-\n| 314     || \"[[Whom Gods Destroy (Star Trek: The Original Series)|Whom Gods Destroy]]\" || One of the mental patients was Andorian\n|-\n| 318     || \"[[The Lights of Zetar]]\" || Two Andorian scholars were present at Memory Alpha at the time of its destruction\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|+ ''[[Star Trek: The Animated Series]]''\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! '''#''' || '''Episode''' || '''Appearance'''\n|-\n| 102     || \"[[Yesteryear (Star Trek: The Animated Series)|Yesteryear]]\" || [[Spock]] replaced by Andorian first officer, Thelin, in alternate timeline\n|-\n| 112     || \"[[The Time Trap]]\" || Andorian on the Elysian Council, plus a member of his old crew in background\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width