ple Blossom]]<ref group=\"note\">The legislation mentions [[Malus coronaria|sweet crabapple]] ('Malus coronaria'') as an example.</ref> <br> ''Malus sp.''\n|1897<ref name=symbols1>{{cite website|title=Michigan's State Symbols|url=http://www.michigan.gov/documents/mhc_mhm_statesymbols2002_47909_7.pdfpagewanted=all|}}</ref>\n|[[File:Crab apple flower.jpg|100px|[[Malus coronaria|Sweet crabapple]] blossom]]\n| A garland of 44 flowers representing the 44 states was made for the World's Columbian Exhibition of 1893 with the Apple Blossom representing Michigan. This inspired Michigan's Legislature to make it official in 1897. <ref name=\"ml\"/>\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state fossils|Fossil]]'''\n|[[Mastodon]] <br> ''Mammut americanum''\n|2002<ref name=\"ml\" />\n|[[File:Mammut americanum.jpg|100px|Mastodon]]\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state mammals|Game Mammal]]'''\n|[[White-Tailed Deer]] <br> ''Odocoileus virginianus''\n|1997<ref name=\"ml\"/>\n|[[File:White-tailed deer.jpg|100px|White-tailed deer]]\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state minerals, rocks, stones and gemstones|Gem]]'''\n|[[Isle Royale greenstone]] <br> ''Chlorastrolite''\n|1972<ref name=\"ml\" />\n|\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state mottos|Motto]]'''\n|''[[Si quaeris peninsulam amoenam circumspice]]''<br/>([[Latin language|Latin]] for \"If you seek a pleasant peninsula, look about you\") <ref>[http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9622_11033_11151-67959--,00.html Michigan's State Facts]</ref>\n|1835\n|\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state reptiles|Reptile]]'''\n||[[Painted turtle]] <br> ''Chrysemys picta''\n|1995<ref name=\"ml\" />\n|[[File:Painted Turtle (14541060047).jpg|100px|Painted turtle]]\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state seals|Seal]]'''\n|[[Great Seal of the State of Michigan]]\n|1835\n|[[File:Seal of Michigan.svg|100px|The [[Great Seal of the State of Michigan]]]] \n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state soils|Soil]]'''\n|[[Kalkaska sand|Kalkaska soil series]]\n|{{dts|1990|12}}<ref name=\"ml\" />\n| \n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state songs|Song]]'''\n|\"[[My Michigan]]\"\n|1937\n|<ref name=\"ml\"/>\n|The resolution passed by the [[Michigan House of Representatives]] specified \"My Michigan\" as \"the official state song,\" but this was changed upon introduction in the [[Michigan Senate|state senate]] to \"an official song.\"  Because the state failed to purchase the copyright from the song's authors, the song is rarely performed today.\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state minerals, rocks, stones and gemstones|Stone]]'''\n|[[Petoskey Stone]] <br> ''Hexagonaria pericarnata''\n|1965\n|[[File:Petoskey stone Hexagonaria percarinata 2.jpg|100px|Petoskey Stone]]<ref name=\"ml\"/>\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state trees|Tree]]'''\n|[[Eastern White Pine]] <br> ''Pinus strobus''\n|1955<ref>{{Citation |title= State Tree, Act 7 of 1955 |date=2002 |publisher= Michigan Legislature |url= https://www.legislature.mi.gov/(S(tzyjbod2n5l151fmpy5yn1uj))/mileg.aspx?page=getObject&objectName=mcl-Act-7-of-1955 |access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title= 2.31 State tree |date=2002 |publisher= Michigan Legislature |url= https://www.legislature.mi.gov/(S(tzyjbod2n5l151fmpy5yn1uj))/mileg.aspx?page=getObject&objectName=mcl-2-31 |access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> \n|[[File:Pinus strobus trees.jpg|100px|Eastern White Pine]]\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state wildflowers|Wildflower]]\n|[[Dwarf Lake Iris]] <br> ''Iris lacustris''\n|1998\n|[[File:Dwarf Lake Iris.jpg|100px|Dwarf Lake Iris]]<ref name=\"ml\" />\n|}\n\n===Other symbols===\n*United States quarter dollar - Michigan 2004[[File:2004 MI Proof.png|128px|top]]\n\n==Proposed==\n/* Proposed */ <ref>Butterfly, The Karner Blue Butterfly for the State Butterfly of Michigan is a bipartisan effort now HB #4661 by Rep. Scott VanSingel R., (Newaygo) and Terry Sabo, D. (Muskegon) the butterfly is endangered and is federally protected. The famous poet Chekov named the butterfly after the city Karner, New York as Chekov discovered this beautiful blue butterfly as well was an avid butterfly collector.<\n* Butterfly - The Michigan Garden Clubs approach Sate Senator Curtis Hertel (D, East Lansing) about making the butterfly the state insect. Thus in March 2019, Hertel and state Rep. Julie Brixie (D, Meridian Twp.) introduced bills to name the black swallowtail butterfly the state butterfly. The prior year saw the Karner blue butterfly .<ref name=\"ml\" />\n* Insect - In 2018, the monarch butterfly was submitted as the official insect by then Senator Jim Marleau. The lady bug was nominated in 2015.<ref name=\"ml\" />\n* Wildflower - the Michigan Wildflower Association put forth the trillium in 1998 as an alternative to the Dwarf Lake Iris as trillium is rare and primarily grows in Michigan.<ref name=\"ml\" />\n* Song - With the lack of knowledge about \"My Michigan\" being an official song, \"[[Michigan, My Michigan]]\" of the Civil War-era is often believe to be the official tune for which it was proposed in 2003 to become but failed. \"Michigan Man\" was proposed in 2014 by Rep. Frank Foster but did not get out of committee.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of U.S. state, district, and territorial insignia]]\n*[[Outline of Michigan]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.michigan.gov/documents/mhc_mhm_statesymbols2002_47909_7.pdf Michigan's State Symbols]\n{{clear}}\n{{Michigan|expanded}}\n{{state symbols|collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of United States state symbols by state|Michigan]]</noinclude>\n[[Category:Michigan-related lists|State symbols]]\n[[Category:Symbols of Michigan| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n[[File:Map of USA MI.svg|thumb|Location of the [[state of Michigan]] in the United States]]\nThe following is a '''list of symbols of the U.S. state of [[Michigan]]'''. Bills to designated state symbols in Michigan are referred to the Government Operations Committee in either chamber.<ref name=\"ml\" />\n\n==State symbols==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! width=12%                  | Type\n! width=21%                  | Symbol\n! width=8%                   | Adopted\n! width=10% class=unsortable | Image\n!                            | Note\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state birds|Bird]]'''\n|[[American robin]] <br> ''Turdus migratorius''\n|align=\"center\"|1931\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Turdus-migratorius-002.jpg|100px|American Robin]]<ref name=\"ml\">{{cite news |last1=Gibbons |first1=Lauren |title=The surprising stories behind Michigan's state symbols |url=https://expo.mlive.com/news/g66l-2019/04/731d5a791e1233/the-surprising-stories-behind-michigans-state-symbols.html |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |work=MLive.com |date=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[Coats of arms of the U.S. states|Coat of Arms]]'''\n|[[Flag of the State of Michigan|Coat of Arms of the State of Michigan]]\n|1835<ref>http://www.michigan.gov/sos/0,4670,7-127-1638_8731-22835--,00.html</ref>\n|[[File:Coat of arms of Michigan.svg|100px|The Coat of Arms of the State of Michigan]]\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state fish|Fish]]'''\n|[[Brook Trout]] <br> ''Salvelinus fontinalis''\n|1988\n|[[File:Brook trout 1918.jpg|100px|Brook trout]]\n| In 1965, the trout was named the official state fish; this was specified as the brook trout in 1988.<ref name=\"ml\"/>\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state flags|Flag]]'''\n|[[Flag of the State of Michigan]]\n|1911\n|[[File:Flag of Michigan.svg|100px|The [[Flag of the State of Michigan]]]]\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state flowers|Flower]]'''\n|[[Malus|Apple Blossom]]<ref group=\"note\">The legislation mentions [[Malus coronaria|sweet crabapple]] ('Malus coronaria'') as an example.</ref> <br> ''Malus sp.''\n|1897<ref name=symbols1>{{cite website|title=Michigan's State Symbols|url=http://www.michigan.gov/documents/mhc_mhm_statesymbols2002_47909_7.pdfpagewanted=all|}}</ref>\n|[[File:Crab apple flower.jpg|100px|[[Malus coronaria|Sweet crabapple]] blossom]]\n| A garland of 44 flowers representing the 44 states was made for the World's Columbian Exhibition of 1893 with the Apple Blossom representing Michigan. This inspired Michigan's Legislature to make it official in 1897. <ref name=\"ml\"/>\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state fossils|Fossil]]'''\n|[[Mastodon]] <br> ''Mammut americanum''\n|2002<ref name=\"ml\" />\n|[[File:Mammut americanum.jpg|100px|Mastodon]]\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state mammals|Game Mammal]]'''\n|[[White-Tailed Deer]] <br> ''Odocoileus virginianus''\n|1997<ref name=\"ml\"/>\n|[[File:White-tailed deer.jpg|100px|White-tailed deer]]\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state minerals, rocks, stones and gemstones|Gem]]'''\n|[[Isle Royale greenstone]] <br> ''Chlorastrolite''\n|1972<ref name=\"ml\" />\n|\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state mottos|Motto]]'''\n|''[[Si quaeris peninsulam amoenam circumspice]]''<br/>([[Latin language|Latin]] for \"If you seek a pleasant peninsula, look about you\") <ref>[http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9622_11033_11151-67959--,00.html Michigan's State Facts]</ref>\n|1835\n|\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state reptiles|Reptile]]'''\n||[[Painted turtle]] <br> ''Chrysemys picta''\n|1995<ref name=\"ml\" />\n|[[File:Painted Turtle (14541060047).jpg|100px|Painted turtle]]\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state seals|Seal]]'''\n|[[Great Seal of the State of Michigan]]\n|1835\n|[[File:Seal of Michigan.svg|100px|The [[Great Seal of the State of Michigan]]]] \n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state soils|Soil]]'''\n|[[Kalkaska sand|Kalkaska soil series]]\n|{{dts|1990|12}}<ref name=\"ml\" />\n| \n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state songs|Song]]'''\n|\"[[My Michigan]]\"\n|1937\n|<ref name=\"ml\"/>\n|The resolution passed by the [[Michigan House of Representatives]] specified \"My Michigan\" as \"the official state song,\" but this was changed upon introduction in the [[Michigan Senate|state senate]] to \"an official song.\"  Because the state failed to purchase the copyright from the song's authors, the song is rarely performed today.\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state minerals, rocks, stones and gemstones|Stone]]'''\n|[[Petoskey Stone]] <br> ''Hexagonaria pericarnata''\n|1965\n|[[File:Petoskey stone Hexagonaria percarinata 2.jpg|100px|Petoskey Stone]]<ref name=\"ml\"/>\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state trees|Tree]]'''\n|[[Eastern White Pine]] <br> ''Pinus strobus''\n|1955<ref>{{Citation |title= State Tree, Act 7 of 1955 |date=2002 |publisher= Michigan Legislature |url= https://www.legislature.mi.gov/(S(tzyjbod2n5l151fmpy5yn1uj))/mileg.aspx?page=getObject&objectName=mcl-Act-7-of-1955 |access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title= 2.31 State tree |date=2002 |publisher= Michigan Legislature |url= https://www.legislature.mi.gov/(S(tzyjbod2n5l151fmpy5yn1uj))/mileg.aspx?page=getObject&objectName=mcl-2-31 |access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> \n|[[File:Pinus strobus trees.jpg|100px|Eastern White Pine]]\n|-\n|'''[[List of U.S. state wildflowers|Wildflower]]\n|[[Dwarf Lake Iris]] <br> ''Iris lacustris''\n|1998\n|[[File:Dwarf Lake Iris.jpg|100px|Dwarf Lake Iris]]<ref name=\"ml\" />\n|}\n\n===Other symbols===\n*United States quarter dollar - Michigan 2004[[File:2004 MI Proof.png|128px|top]]\n\n==Proposed==\n* Butterfly - The Michigan Garden Clubs approach Sate Senator Curtis Hertel (D, East Lansing) about making the butterfly the state insect. Thus in March 2019, Hertel and state Rep. Julie Brixie (D, Meridian Twp.) introduced bills to name the black swallowtail butterfly the state butterfly. The prior year saw the Karner blue butterfly .<ref name=\"ml\" />\n* Insect - In 2018, the monarch butterfly was submitted as the official insect by then Senator Jim Marleau. The lady bug was nominated in 2015.<ref name=\"ml\" />\n* Wildflower - the Michigan Wildflower Association put forth the trillium in 1998 as an alternative to the Dwarf Lake Iris as trillium is rare and primarily grows in Michigan.<ref name=\"ml\" />\n* Song - With the lack of knowledge about \"My Michigan\" being an official song, \"[[Michigan, My Michigan]]\" of the Civil War-era is often believe to be the official tune for which it was proposed in 2003 to become but failed. \"Michigan Man\" was proposed in 2014 by Rep. Frank Foster but did not get out of committee.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of U.S. state, district, and territorial insignia]]\n*[[Outline of Michigan]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.michigan.gov/documents/mhc_mhm_statesymbols2002_47909_7.pdf Michigan's State Symbols]\n{{clear}}\n{{Michigan|expanded}}\n{{state symbols|collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of United States state symbols by state|Michigan]]</noinclude>\n[[Category:Michigan-related lists|State symbols]]\n[[Category:Symbols of Michigan| ]]\n", "name_user": "LoriEslick", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProposed:<ref>Butterfly, The Karner Blue Butterfly for the State Butterfly of Michigan is a bipartisan effort now HB #4661 by Rep. Scott VanSingel R., (Newaygo) and Terry Sabo, D. (Muskegon) the butterfly is endangered and is federally protected, and the poet Chekov named the butterfly after the city Karner, New York as Chekov was a butterfly collector.</ref>", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Michigan_state_symbols"}
